@NODE "Mail_6" "Re: 3d stuff"
Date: Fri, 9 Oct 1998 10:31:33 BST
From: Steven Dobbs <kaum6@central.susx.ac.uk>
Subject: Re: 3d stuff





On Fri, 2 Oct 1998 00:33:14 +0100  Wright J.A wrote:

> From: Wright J.A <J.A.Wright@rhbnc.ac.uk>
> Date: Fri, 2 Oct 1998 00:33:14 +0100 
> Subject: 3d stuff
> To: 'Blitz Mailing List' <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
> 
> hi blitzers,
>                ok i`m going to try to do some 3d stuff, first i think
> it`s good to start with a simple cube, but i really want to progress to
> do more detailed objects like space ships and stuff (obviously)  8)
> the problem is that i can`t decide whether to use Cartesian co-ord
> system, or Spherical Polar co-ords to represent the points that make up
> an object.....   any with any experience in this field care to offer
> some advantages and disadvantages of each??  the main factor i care
> about here is speed of the calculations.....  
> 
> thanks,
> James

-Actually, I had never thought to use spherical polar coords for object deffinitions: does this offer any advantages? Is 
something mathematically easier to do, like alignments or something which became fairly complicated in my routines-

I am completing a collection of 3d routines and a 3d object editor for a 3d game myself (eventually to be done in C). What I 
do is use cartesian coords to represent the points of the ships. This has the advantage of enabling you to translate the 
object easier and therefor faster using simple additions of vectors and what have you. My routines are incomplete as I 
havent finalised the object format, but are functional as they can align coords to things.

my 3d to 2d point conversion algorithm is based on cartesian to spherical coords, this has definate advantages: It solves 
one of the problem of drawing objects partly ahead of you and partly infront of you, as a large -z makes for large sperical 
polar angles (other people and graphics cards I think use division by z perhaps, it is probably faster but requires a 
little cunning with the polygon drawing algorithm)

My advice for the depth sorting algorithm seems a little controversial; graphics cards do it based on the z-cord, but I believe 
there are significant speed advantages to be had from spherical polar coords despite what everybody has said on the blitz 
list about it. The advantage is that its a distance sort not a relative z cord sort which means that the distance sort is roughly 
valid for several frames and isnt screwed up by viewpoint realignment. 

then there are the sorting algorithms. Most people choose the generally extremely fast quick sort method described in 
many general computing textbooks. but I choose to try the simpler but less efficient bubble sort. I imagine that this may 
overtake the quick sort method because the quicksort method is designed for sorting arrays of very unsorted data (this 
makes it clearly the best for sorting the mess that happens with view realignment on the z distance to a point) but since the 
actual distance stays very similar for the majority of polygons in a large space, then a single bubble sort pass may be all 
that is needed to correct the sorted array. points near the bottom of the list may need to be sorted more frequently 
(because they are nearer). Also with bubble sort on spherical radius distance you might not actually need to recalulate the 
sort for several frames, possibly making it worth while to use the trig functions (or look up tables on slower machines) to get 
the speed advantages of the sort algorithm. But maby not, I wont know till I try my chosen method.

If you'd like, or anybody else, to have my working and tested 3d routines then ask. I should first comment on what use they 
are. They can translate points, rotate points, set up orthoganal basis vectors (I think thats the right word) ie functions which 
use these functions to perform rotation of these vectors which describe the local coord system of the object as 3 unit 
vectors sticking out orthoganaly. functions to perform relative movements. And to obtain conversions for global to local and 
visa versa. If anybody wants to have a look at these functions and statements then I'll send them to you and explain how 
they work.

Also I might need some help, I use a rotation method to obtain certain information which I imagine might be better done 
through matix operations, alas I did not do well on my linear algerbra course.

also it would be great if that PPC thing got off the ground and if it had stuff for gfx cards too, because at the moment 
everything 3d has to be done in C really.

Dobbs

;---------
projects:
Ace2d [......... ] 90%ish.
(a simple bip from above game, just needs simple AI to be added)

Star Stalker [.         ] 10%ish  It will take bloody ages
(wing commanderish game using artificial life to make killing more fun)

Also on a different note, my game is in the earliest stages, so advice on plot could be nice; what do you lot prefer? humans 
going on a rampage across the galaxy anoyed at aliens using human derived life as fanatical shock troops, food, sport and 
slavery of every description - humans on the run fighting back against the Star Stalkers, a species which claims the galaxy 
and extinguishes all technological competitors that it encounters (Our radio broadcasts leaking into space make us stand 
out like a frightened lambs where theres no cover when others had learnt to be silent and stealthy) - humans going against 
another empire (Wing commander) or civil war (Colony Wars on the playstation) or something I havent thought of. Ideas on 
this would be nice since I'd like to start some of the opening sequences soon and to think up spaceship designs and what 
have you.




