From: Stephen Fellner <sfell@xtra.co.nz>
Date: 10 October 1998 07:55
Subject: 3d stuff...


>Hi all !
>
>I've heard somebody asking about 3d stuff in blitz...
>
>Well, the advantage of using polar coordinates is that rotation becomes
dead
>easy. But plotting becomes somewhat slower, as your polar coordinates must
be
>converted into rectangular before you can do the 3D plotting. However,
there's
>a way to rotate points in 3D, directly in rectangular without having to
>convert back-forth from polar. Although I only have the formulas for 2D
>rotation at the moment, it shouldn't be very difficult to extend them to
3d...
>
>I've written a program that plots a 3D torus that you can move around the
>screen... only wireframe at the moment, no fancy phong shading etc, but
it's
>still nice :)
>
>Cheers,
>Stephen
>



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_10" "3Drot, etc."
From: Stephen Fellner <sfell@xtra.co.nz>
Date: Sat, 24 Oct 1998 14:09:57 +1200
Subject: 3Drot, etc.

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.

This message was composed on an Amiga using the YAM mailer.
YAM is available at http://bitcom.ch/~mbeck/

--BOUNDARY.7601.2862.122697320.2

Hello Everyone !

I've got the 3D rot thingy going... it doesn't use the fancy matrix stuff yet,
but works...

Here's the example program... it's a similar program to Plotter3D, it plots a
mathematical formula and you can move around it... all the values, like the
zoom, perspective, scaling, the formulas, etc. must be modified within the
program listing before compiling... I wanted to implement realtime zooming,
etc. but the inkey$ doesn't seem to work, unless you have a window open. And
I've used a pretty strange double-buffering, simply opening two screens, and
swapping between them :) This doesn't work with windows on the screen, as
they'll be automatically activated every time, really slowing down the thing
and they sortof redraw when activated... unfortunately this was the only way I
could implement double-buffering in Amiga mode... sure, it's a piece of cake
in blitz mode, but you can't use a 640x480 multiscan screen in blitz mode...
and my multisync monitor can't display 15 Khz anyway :-(

By the way, doesn't blitz have the ability to compile some code during program
executions ? I've written a texture generator program before, that generates a
texture from mathametical formulae... and you can generate some really nice
textures... but the formula had to be entered from the listing before
compiling, ie. I couldn't make a compact program that would allow the user to
enter the formula into a string gadget, and the program would interpret the
formula and generate the code accordingly... This would require some serious
programming...

Anyway, I still think is't a pretty cool program... even if a little slow...
you can enable/disable the x and y grids, so if you disable both, it draws
dots instead of lines, and if you enable both, it draws a net... (ie. both x
and y grids)... You can also change the x/y resolution, ie. how many points
you want... but careful you don't go too high, as you might be sitting there
for an hour for the first frame to appear :)

Enjoy... :)

-- 
Stephen


