@NODE "Mail_12" "Amiga Programming Futures"
 with ESMTP id <0F0Z00ID3PN53T@hermes.ucd.ie> for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie;
 Sat, 17 Oct 1998 22:13:54 +0100 (BST)
 <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Sat, 17 Oct 1998 16:07:29 -0500 (CDT)
Date: Sat, 17 Oct 1998 16:05:11 +0500
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Subject: Amiga Programming Futures

On 15-Oct-98, Paul flashed:
-clip-
>not interested in these copper, blitter, or sprite screens. TBH I
>thought that this kind of hardware bashing went out with the A500.
-clip-
> 
>> >I just don't think there is much future in
>> >blitter-based chunky screens.

>I don't know. For somebody somewhere it might have a use but it will
>only be a minority thing and what with the shift to graphics cards,
>c2p routines of any kind aren't going to live much longer.

  Paul, please don't think I am flaming you ideas or choices, but I
want to use this opportunity to give some of the programers here
another point of view about the legacy Amiga situation.

  I am convinced (at least it is certainly true here in the midwest USA)
that very few legacy Amiga owners own (and possibly never will own) a
graphics card or PPC card.  In the city I live in I know MANY Amiga
owners and I am the only one of them who owns a graphics card (but I
have no PPC card).  I purchased both Opalvision and Cybervision and have
gotten almost no value from either one of them.  Both lost support soon
after I purchased them.  Most of the Amiga owners I know (about 80 of them)
have upgraded ram, drives and cpus but not graphics and no PPC.  Most of
theme never see the discussions of the more active of us because they do
not frequent the internet.  Most have NOT purchased windoze machines because
their Amigas still suffice and money doesn't grow on trees.  Most own
a game platform (usually PlayStation) but still play some games on their
Amigas (if they play games at all).  Most buy little software because they
consider it to expensive or not enticing enough or not needed enough for
what added value it might offer.  For the same reasons, most own few games
for their PlayStations.  Most would buy software if a good enough appeal was
made in a media that they had available.  Most don't particularly want a
windoze setup, but are kind of hanging in limbo waiting to see what the
Amiga will do.  Some of these people havn't got excited about computing
since AGA came out, some longer than that.  Quite a few others have
purchased windoze machines but aren't particularly thrilled with them and
still keep their Amigas around and dust them off occasionaly to play an
old game or do artwork, and to wish that the Amiga had continued.  Many
of these people of both groups don't even know the Amiga isn't dead.  They
aren't on-line, they get no magazines, they don't attend Amiga club
meetings (I am president of our local group so often look up some of the
past Amiga users) and of course there are no local Amiga sales points to keep
them informed.
  Most of these people are still interested in software for their Amigas if
something fun or useful comes along and they are made aware of it.  Those of
us on the internet who are in communication with each other are getting the
mistaken impression that we are the only (and therefor representative) Amiga
owners left.  FALSE!!!  In my studied estimation, there are still over a
MILLION Amigas in use.  Amigas seldom get thrown away, someone always buys
them (cheap sometimes) or has them given to them.  I have had a surprising
number of encounters with NEW Amiga users who got an Amiga cheap or free
and now wants software for it but is told at the local chain store that there
is none available.
  I want to make software for these people and figure out how to make it
available to them.  The market potential is still huge, it is the total lack
of product exposure that is the problem.  Legacy Amigas will be around LONG
after the present-day windoze machines are scrapped because the Amigas are
easier to set up and use without support, and because of the vast freely-
distributable software base, and becaues of the sentimental attachment
which many feel for Amiga.

  OLD AMIGAS NEVER DIE, THEY JUST PASS ON (and on, and on)


  Most users of old Amigas are still interested in the platform and therefor
any good software for it.  Many still dream however of that new model Amiga
powerhouse which never came to be.  Boy are THEY going to be surprised!
  I believe a LOT of people will be surprised at how many people will come
out of the woodwork when the NEW Amiga anouncements and advertising hit the
media.  This will include also a lot of disgruntled windoze owners who never
had an Amiga but want a change.


  So what am I saying here?

  The legacy Amiga market may never grow big again but if it doesn't it will
be for lack of effort on the part of developers and lack of advertising, not
for lack of potential customers.  There are MANY types of businesses which
thrive with much smaller potential customer bases.

  The NEW Amiga market WILL thrive because it will get a lot of press
and will be advertised well, as well as because the NEW Amigas themselves
will be sensational.  The campain which Gateway-backed Amiga Inc. and
Amiga Int. are planning along with other major players will hit the market
HARD.  This alone wil also garner much free press exposure.  But couple
that with the sensation which a major new challenge to windoze is going
to create and there will be few who will not be made aware of the NEW
Amiga.  The NEW Amiga is going to sell very well indeed at the outset.
What happens after that is at least partially up to programers like us.
  Opportunity awaits NOW in the Amiga legacy market, and will soon be
knocking very loudly in the NEW Amiga market.

  I for one intend to enjoy BOTH challenges (and make some money).

How about you-all?


Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_13" "Re: Amiga Programming Futures"
 Wed, 21 Oct 1998 08:53:44 -0600 (CST)
Date: Wed, 21 Oct 1998 08:53:43 -0600 (CST)
