@NODE "Mail_43" "Blitz PPC"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Wed, 07 Oct 1998 15:04:42 +1200
Subject: Blitz PPC

On 07-Oct-98, Paul wrote:
 
>There was only one thing I wanted to talk of in the past two days and
>it was regarding PPC blitz because I was looking a little at getting a
>ppc card and blizzardvision. But it's not very likely at the mo.
 
  Well, it seems that Phoenix has fallen through, as far as I can tell. 
I'm thinking of having a little tinker with doing a PPC Blitz, starting
off small and making a simple CLI compiler, and then putting in
libraries support later. At first it will put out PPC assembler (as I
don't have much knowledge of Hunk structures at the moment), which
could then be put through a PPC assembler like PhxAss. This would also
mean you could use the assembler's debugging tools to start off with. 
    Now /don't/ you all get your hopes up! As I suffer from Chronic
Fatigue Syndrome (M.E.), and get tired easily so I can't do a lot of
work at once. I seem to be recovering at the moment so I might be able
to get something out in a couple of months time, assuming I recover
enough of course :)
  Why do a PPC version of Blitz- well I hate C (and Java uses the same
horrid notion!!), and there will be no Basic on future Amiga's for the
present. So it's either use C, or write your own Basic! :-) Plus it's a
wicked challenge, and I love challenges :-)
  It would also end up supporting MMC and OS5.0. It's specs would end up
being basically the same as Phoenix's- ie: fix up all the problems with
Blitz. Maybe later I might put in inheritance for local variables (for
functions, like in Java). I would probably start off with it making 68k
assem, but I don't think I'd bother with 68k support later on.
  And the name, well I like Phoenix, but the problem is, that everywhere
you look there's companies using the name (including software products),
so I find it a bit unoriginal. The other name that was competing with
Phoenix was `Magma' (someone on the list came up with it- I can't
remember who), and I really like the ring of it :)  Of course if the
rights to the name Blitz could be got cheaply from Guildhall, I'd prefer
it to be Blitz 3- but I don't think that would happen :-/
  What would the compiler be written in? Well Blitz of course! And as
soon as enough work was done on it, you could run it through itself and
compile using the PPC! Rather incestuous I know ;-)
  And yes, I would obviously need a lot of help from you lot, especially
to do libraries, docs etc. I would like to try to make libs
automatically with a program like FDconvert, but to put it into a format
like Frederic's NScreen.lib. I don't know how feasible it would be, and
some libs will still have to be done by hand anyhow.
  I eventually would like it to be a commercial product- otherwise I
don't think it will end up happening- not enough motivation to do it,
otherwise. It will be PD to start off with, and people helping would be
rewarded according to how much work they end up doing (this would have
to be addressed in more detail in future), and I don't think any money
would be forthcoming until MMC machines hit the stores, so it would be a
future issue. In the mean time we might be able to keep Blitz from
becoming extinct!
  For the record, I wouldn't be doing it just for the money, I also want
to keep Blitz going! If the Amiga succeeds, them it would be a very
worthwhile project for everyone involved. Also, I have no money myself
so I couldn't pay anyone wages etc beforehand.
 
  Again, remember this isn't definite- I'll keep you posted if I get
something going :)

  Seeya- Anton

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz> ICQ #15349462 
      A500,DF1:,0.5MC,8.5MF,60HDD,WB3.1 &1.3/2.0 
    A1200 WB3.0,25/040,200/PPC,CD-Rom - From 1-280 Mips in 15 secs!
        My ICQ page: <http://wwp.mirabilis.com/15349462>
    Project: UDP_Chat [99%]- an Internet multi-player code, test-bed 
      for my game Pyro-Mid. - Aminet: dev/basic/UDP_Chat.lha (V2.1)
         <http://www.ww.co.nz/home/anton/> 



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_44" "Re: Blitz PPC"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 7 Oct 1998 13:11:00 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Wed, 07 Oct 1998 12:58:28 +0000
Subject: Re: Blitz PPC

Hi,

>> There was only one thing I wanted to talk of in the past two days and
>> it was regarding PPC blitz because I was looking a little at getting a
>> ppc card and blizzardvision. But it's not very likely at the mo.
> 
> Well, it seems that Phoenix has fallen through, as far as I can tell. 
> I'm thinking of having a little tinker with doing a PPC Blitz, starting
> off small and making a simple CLI compiler, and then putting in
> libraries support later.

I was part of he Phoenix discission group and I personaly feel that
the project went to "sleep" until a group (or single developer) turned up
to offer solid programming/development support. Most of the Phoenix
members were good Blitz (often expert) programmers and knowlegable
with other systems and languages. The only thing the Phoenix team
lacked was someone (or group of peope) who had the knowlege, time
and patience to put all the ideas into reality. I'm sure we could have
spent more time planning out the project but (speaking from my
own point of view only) it wasn't easy to put all the ideas together
without the assurance of a solid end product. This was made worse by
the fact that some of us had extremely busy schedules with other
projects.. I was in the last 2 months of Foundation development! :)

> At first it will put out PPC assembler (as I
> don't have much knowledge of Hunk structures at the moment), which
> could then be put through a PPC assembler like PhxAss. This would also
> mean you could use the assembler's debugging tools to start off with. 

I would like to see something happen with your project. Even if it's
VERY small to start off with.

>  Why do a PPC version of Blitz- well I hate C (and Java uses the same
> horrid notion!!), and there will be no Basic on future Amiga's for the
> present. So it's either use C, or write your own Basic! :-) Plus it's a
> wicked challenge, and I love challenges :-)

Thats what it's all about isn't it! :)

>  And yes, I would obviously need a lot of help from you lot, especially
> to do libraries, docs etc. I would like to try to make libs
> automatically with a program like FDconvert, but to put it into a format
> like Frederic's NScreen.lib. I don't know how feasible it would be, and
> some libs will still have to be done by hand anyhow.

Considering the fact that the end result is to provide code for
high spec systems (most future computers/Amiga NG etc..) you can
probably live with a *little* overhead here and there so I would
suggest you make all the libs in raw blitz code. This would allow
everyone to help you and ensure future compatability for all cpu's.

> I eventually would like it to be a commercial product- otherwise I
> don't think it will end up happening- not enough motivation to do it,
> otherwise.

If the project takes off, it gets used (in early PD form) to create software
that gets *used* and software that is *popular* then I'm sure some
publishers would take a serious look at it.

Cheers,

-- 
Paul Burkey <--> http://burkey.home.ml.org <-->



@ENDNODE
