@NODE "Mail_46" "Re: Blitz PPC"
From: =?iso-8859-1?Q?Fr=E9d=E9ric?= Laboureur <alphasnd@hol.fr>
Date: Wed, 07 Oct 1998 19:33:17 +0100
Organization: Fantaisie Software
Subject: Re: Blitz PPC
Encoding: quoted-printable

    Hi Anton, =


>  Well, it seems that Phoenix has fallen through, as far as I can tell. =

> I'm thinking of having a little tinker with doing a PPC Blitz, starting=

> off small and making a simple CLI compiler..

    May be you will be happy to know that I work since 2 months (not lot =
of
free time to allow...) at the PhenX project. I've already done a 68000
compiler (nearly all opcodes are supported). It's speed is very slow (abo=
ut
350 lines/secs on 68030/50) but its done in Blitz and not optimized.

    It's particularity is that is compile one time a code and after, it
compile ONLY the lines which need it:

    MOVE #0, d1 don't need to be recompiled at each pass.

    Most of my libraries are ready to be used with this ASM, which could =
have
very optimized support for Screen, Windows, GadTools... As this language =
is
new, it will be as efficient as possible, without be 100% compatible with=
 old
blitz sources (old gadgets are obsolete, GadTools will be the standard fo=
r
example..)

    The things which lacks for now is the HIGH Level langage. The idea is=
tranform each HIGH level lnagage lines into a series of ASM ones.

    Ie: If a=3D0 Then o=3D0

    a4, store the variable base,
    a5, store the library base (up to ~65000/4 lib loadable in the same t=
ime

    In ASM, it would be like that:

    CMP x(a4), #0
    BNE .End
    MOVE #0, y(a4)
=2EEnd:

    The big advantage is that you can generate indifferentely PPC ASM or =
68000
ASM. Use the appropriate compiler after :-).

    What to say more ? May be it will be ready one day :-). I hope. But T=
hink
that a line like: If a=3D0 AND (b=3D0 or c=3D1) OR p=3D0 isn't easy to tr=
ansforme in
ASM
lines. I don't have found any routine to do that.

    A Visual Module will be integrated in the soft. (I'm boring to do an
interface in 2 hours using the code instead of 5 min using the mouse, lik=
e on
Visual Basic (M$)) :-).

    Regards,

                        Fred.

