>    It's particularity is that is compile one time a code and after, it
>compile ONLY the lines which need it:

>    MOVE #0, d1 don't need to be recompiled at each pass.

  I assume you mean that it only compiles/assembles changes in the
source code, to speed things up :)

>    Most of my libraries are ready to be used with this ASM, which
could
>have
>very optimized support for Screen, Windows, GadTools... As this
language
>is
>new, it will be as efficient as possible, without be 100% compatible
>with old
>blitz sources (old gadgets are obsolete, GadTools will be the standard
>for
>example..)

  Yes, there are several things like that in Blitz that need changing!
Like having unsigned variables, and changing the curly {} brackets for
functions to square [] brackets, to make it easier to read.

>    The things which lacks for now is the HIGH Level langage. The idea
>is to
>tranform each HIGH level lnagage lines into a series of ASM ones.

  Yes, that was what I was going to start with.

>    Ie: If a=3D0 Then o=3D0

>    a4, store the variable base,
>    a5, store the library base (up to ~65000/4 lib loadable in the same
>time
>:-)

>    In ASM, it would be like that:

>    CMP x(a4), #0
>    BNE .End
>    MOVE #0, y(a4)
>.End:

>    The big advantage is that you can generate indifferentely PPC ASM
or
>68000
>ASM. Use the appropriate compiler after :-).

  Yep, that's what I was thinking- you have a deflibs for each CPU, and
also a data file for the control/variable structures for each CPU as
well- then you just load in the appropriate files for the CPU being
compiled for. Then you can make some files for the MMC/OS5 the same way.

>    What to say more ? May be it will be ready one day :-). I hope. But
