>         commands and syntax, making sure that only the core
>         instructions defined in the first macro lib.
> 
> Make a PPC and 68K version of the assembler and core macro library.

Perhaps someone could explain in more detail quite what a macro 
assembler is?  Sounds great for anything I would want to use it for, 
but there must be some disadvantages..

An macro (i.e. in a traditional assembler) is inserted every time you 
use that command, i.e. if the command is "print", the code for 
printing is inserted in the source at every occurrence.  Is this the 
sort of macro we're talking about?  If it is, what about the obvious 
problem of bloat?  Or are the macros treated as subroutines - in 
which case, how does this differ from any other language?

I'm obviously missing something :)



