@NODE "Mail_99" "CPU Blit, C2P, and other issues that have been discussed a million times..."
From: Jake Frederick <gonzo@acadia.net>
Date: Sat, 10 Oct 1998 16:47:18 +0500
Subject: CPU Blit, C2P, and other issues that have been discussed a million times...

    I am going to write a game a that requires a large background bit map that
is scrolled around with several large shapes blitted on top of it. I would
like it to be OS friendly and gfx card compatible while utilizing fast ram.
What would the best way to go about this be? I know I need to implement some
sort of CPU blitting, but exactly are the advantages of using a chunky to
planer rountine? Is it primarily for a speed increase? Would it be wise to use
both CPU blitting and C2P for maximum preformance? 
    Although I have been pogramming games for years I have always distanced
myself from the very technical aspects, focusing mostly on the game design
itself. I started when I was very young and picked up a bad habit of simply
taking example pieces of code and stringing them together until I had
something that represented a game. I would like to finally understand some of
the concepts I have missed because I think once I did I am capable of
producing some very high quality games. However, I find the examples of the
things that interest me the most (CPU blitting, C2P, etc.) hard to grasp.
While I get the basic concept, it just doesn't quite fit into a logical form
that I can apply to anything. I would appreciate it greatly if some of the
more advanced programmers on the list could help me put together on some sort
of reference guide for people like me trying to understand some of these more
complex concepts. I would like to make a web page for this sort of thing and
possibly publish a few articles in Amazing Computing, the US magazine that I
currently writing game reviews for. I'm sorry that I went a little bit off the
original subject, it probably should have been two messages, but it just sort
came to me this way as I was typing. Any ideas or examples would be greatly
appreciated...
-- 
-If the doors of perception were cleansed everything would appear to man as it
truly is, infinite.-



@ENDNODE
