@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_105" "Re: data"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 06 Oct 1998 22:18:18 -0500
Subject: Re: data

Hi Andrew,

On 06-Oct-98, Andrew Drays wrote:
> 
> ok dudes.. I know you probly covered this.. but I need a crash course on
> data.. in specific, what I'm about to cover.. here's my dilemma.. I have a
> bumch of constant data... I have set like this..
> 
> 
> errn$(1)="100"
> errt$(1)="SETDATA"
> errn$(2)="101"
> errt$(2)="CONNECTBAD"
> 
> etc.. like that except its 135 times! and all different data..

> my question.. is.. is there a more efficient way to handle this?
> 
> like setting them up as data$ statements and spo on.. and is I set the data
> arrarys ad data statements.. how do I access thos data statments?
> 
> the entire concept of data statements and such is ver confusing to me.. 
> 
> I know all the data I have could probly be set up in dtata statements and
> handled a LOT quicker.. but, HOW??

Just think of the Data statements the same as reading data in from an outside
file.
The only difference is that the file is INSIDE your own program:

Dim errn$(135)
Dim errt$(135)

For i = 1 to 135
  Read errt$(i)
Next

Data$ "SETDATA","CONNECTBAD","etc","etc","etc"
Data$ (keep doing for all 135 strings)

For i = 1 to 135
  Read errn$(i)
Next

Data$ "100","101", (and so on)

You can also do the same for data using bytes, words, etc.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_106" "Re: data"
From: Blitzwing <blitzwing@goldweb.com.au>
Date: Wed, 07 Oct 1998 18:18:09 +1000
Subject: Re: data

I got a slighty more efficient way of doing it :

> Dim errn$(135)
> Dim errt$(135)

> For i = 1 to 135
>  Read errt$(i) , errn$(135)
> Next

> Data$ "SETDATA","100","CONNECTBAD","101","etc","etc","etc"
> Data$ (keep doing for all 135 strings amd numbers alternating)

Also If those numbers are constant going up ie errn$(135)=234
then use errn$(i)=str$(i+99)

There are more efficient ways of doing this, email me if you need one

Blitzwing



@ENDNODE
