          Tue, 27 Oct 1998 10:03:50 +0000
          27 Oct 98 10:03:52 +0000
From: "S.J.CROY" <ap6013@qmw.ac.uk>
Organization: University of London (QMW)
Date: Tue, 27 Oct 1998 10:03:21 +0000
encoding: 7BIT
Subject: Re: Enforcer hits


Hello Paul

> Hi,
> 
> >     On another note, this isn`t really Blitz related, but how 
> > does the Save, Use, Cancel options of Prefs programs work?  
> > Obvoiulsy Cancel is just ignore, but what of Save and Use?
> > I think Save writes the prefs file to ENVARC: and makes a copy in 
> > RAM:ENV/   and Use just copies it to RAM:Env/.  Is this correct?
> 
> I use these buttons in the preferences for Foundation. The Use button will
> save the preferences to ram: which is where the main game will first look.
> The Save button will save to the prefs/ directory. The Envarc: idea is
> similar but I don't really like the concept of the Envarc: directory.
> Unless you use the handy startup hack HappyEnv you'd end up with a huge
> amount of wasted memory with all the programs that dump prefs files on
> there. I waste a few minutes each month clearing out the crap from the
> Env-archive directory. It's not exactly elegant computing.
> 

Ok, so probably the best thing to do is to save the prefs file in the 
same dir as the program.  Then when the program loads up, it 
looks in Ram: first and see if there`s a prefs file.  If it doesn`t find 
one then it just loads then one in the same dir.

Thanks a lot
Steven



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_119" "Re: Enforcer hits"
From: hotcakes@abacus.net.au
Date: 27 Oct 1998 19:58:04 EDT
Subject: Re: Enforcer hits

BU>Unless you use the handy startup hack HappyEnv you'd end up with a
BU>huge amount of wasted memory with all the programs that dump prefs
BU>files on there. I waste a few minutes each month clearing out the crap
BU>from the Env-archive directory. It's not exactly elegant computing.

<shrugs> I quite like the ENV: idea =]

My ENV: directory is only wasting 200k of mem atm, I figure I can spare
that =]

Sure, it's a junkyard, but it's better than cluttering all the other
usual places before OS2 was around (ie S:, L:, Devs:, SYS:)...  the only
better place I can think of to save your prefs files would be in
PROGDIR:...  that way when you delete the program you don't still have
the prefs junk lying around the place, if the program had it's own
directory...

