From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 05 Oct 1998 19:56:02 -0500
Subject: Re: Entering password

Hi Everyone,

On 05-Oct-98, Anton Reinauer wrote:
> On 06-Oct-98, amorel wrote:
>> On 05-Oct-98, Paul wrote:
> 
>> C=Design a custom font that contains only *'s instead of alphabetical
>> C=characters.
>> C=?
> 
>> C=Or you could set foreground and background colours the same?
> 
>> No, no. Its way easier and better(as it doesnt even show the amount of
>> chars in a password) to not show the chars at all. In Borland Pascal I
>> always do char:=readkey(this doesnt echo the char to screen) and then 
>> check every char typed and they all have to match. There will be a way 
>> to do this in blitz too, but I cant be bothered to look it up.
> 
>  Yes, yes :-)  It's good for the user to have feedback on how many
> characters they've typed in, as they're typing in a password blind
> otherwise, and can make mistakes easily!

I agree!  I make enough mistakes with the "*"'s.

Why not use Inkey$ to get the characters, then use a text gadget instead of a
string gadget for the output, and put another "*" in it at each input?

=========================================

While we are on the subject of passwords, a personal view:

My computer is in my home.  The only people who would see the password are me,
my family, and friends.  It is easy for me to wait or ask people to leave for
a minute if I want to keep a password private - and most of the time I
wouldn't care who sees it anyway.  So, I would rather have the option to see
the actual characters I am typing, rather than just "****".  Maybe something
you could set in the program prefs?

I think this would be a useful option many people would appreciate.



                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




