Le 05-Oct-98, amorel a =E9crit:

>No, no. Its way easier and better(as it doesnt even show the amount of
>chars in a password) to not show the chars at all. In Borland Pascal I
>always do char:=3Dreadkey(this doesnt echo the char to screen) and then =

>check every char typed and they all have to match. There will be a way =

>to do this in blitz too, but I cant be bothered to look it up.

Hi ,

I had a look to your problem and it seems the source I attach here do wan=
t you
want. I don't know if it's the best way. For example, it's possible WaitE=
vent
is not the best choice (better than Event or not ?).

The source is not completely clear, but I haven't the ASCII code. So you =
will
have to finish the work yourself.

Regards,

                                          Mathias

-- =

email       : mathias.p@wanadoo.fr
site web : http://perso.wanadoo.fr/supersport/


--BOUNDARY.7585.2117.269572920.1

; Ask a password printing a * per character
; Demande un mot de passe en affichant * pour chaque caractere
; Date : 06/10/98
; By   : Cyanure
; Other: For you, Amorel ;-)

WBStartup
NoCli

FindScreen 0

Window 0,20,20,400,200,$1000,"Password ...",1,2
Print "Enter password : "

chaine$=""
Repeat
  ev.l=WaitEvent
  If ev.l=$400
    car$=Inkey$
    ;If car$ is a letter, a number, or codes such a # or $ ...
    ;You have to look at the ASCII code. Sorry, I haven't ! If you don't do
    ; that: escape, Ctrl, Alt, ... will be consider as characters
      Print "*"
      chaine$+car$
    ;EndIf
  EndIf
Until car$=Chr$(13)                     ; until you validate pressing
                                        ; the 'return key'

; If you need, removes the last char (if it's the 'return' char)
;chaine$=UnLeft$(chaine$,1)

NPrint ""
NPrint chaine$

Delay_ 100
Free Window 0

End



--BOUNDARY.7585.2117.269572920.1--




