@NODE "Mail_151" "find devices+line drawing"
From: "Wright J.A" <J.A.Wright@rhbnc.ac.uk>
Subject: find devices+line drawing
Date: Tue, 13 Oct 1998 14:55:46 +0100

hello again,
               just 2 questions here,  

first, how can i get a list of the names of disks currently available, for
my app to display so the user can select one? 

second,  in a game i`ve coded a rotating 3d wireframe cube, it is only drawn
1 colour at the moment using the Line command, however i`m drawing it on a
screen which is 2 bitplanes depth (4 cols). What i want to do is make it so
when a line intercepts another, that point of overlap is drawn in a brighter
colour...  i think i need to set up the palette so that col0 is Black and
Cols1-3 are the colour of my cube from darker to lighter.... but i think i
need to change the mode of the line draw so that it OR`s the bitplanes?? is
that right???  
and how the hell do you do it???????

thanks,
james
        
             


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_152" "Re: find devices+line drawing"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Tue, 13 Oct 1998 14:41:45 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 13 Oct 98 15:40:42 +0000
Subject: Re: find devices+line drawing
Encoding: 7bit

> second,  in a game i`ve coded a rotating 3d wireframe cube, it is only drawn
> 1 colour at the moment using the Line command, however i`m drawing it on a
> screen which is 2 bitplanes depth (4 cols). What i want to do is make it so
> when a line intercepts another, that point of overlap is drawn in a brighter
> colour...  i think i need to set up the palette so that col0 is Black and
> Cols1-3 are the colour of my cube from darker to lighter.... but i think i
> need to change the mode of the line draw so that it OR`s the bitplanes?? is
> that right???  
> and how the hell do you do it???????

I'm no expert on this but the way I'd do it in 4 colours is to sort
out the drawing order. Any lines which are the `back' of the object
should be drawn in the first bitplane, and any lines that are the
`front' of the object should be drawn in the second bitplane. You
should then set the palette so that colour 1 and colour 2 are
basically the same but that colour 3 is the one brighter for where
things overlap. By `front' and `back' I basically mean that if you
take the start and end positions in an clockwise direction and the
starting point is further left than the ending point then the line is
`behind' the object. The same applies the other way around for
detecting a `front' line. Basically the back lines and the front lines
overlap. If you should ever want two back lines to overlap or two
front lines to overlap then you either need more bitplanes or some
strange drawing mode but I don't think it's an OR, or even if that's
possible.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
