Subject: gfx car programming


Does anybody know how many pixel per second can be done using wplot

Also, does anybody find that when windows programing that their memory drops like a sinking ship. Perhaps somebody 
has found this before and relised a way out of it or that they were doing something wrong as I might be. But It seems that 
any program I do which runs on Workbench just sinks as the memory goes down like a countdown. Please help because it 
will be impossible to do anything in blitz if I cant solve this problem

Dobbs




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_181" "Re: gfx car programming"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    12 Oct 98 15:20:08 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University
Date: Mon, 12 Oct 1998 15:19:57 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: gfx car programming

On 12 Oct 98, at 15:06, Steven Dobbs' memory collapsed under the weight of=

> Does anybody know how many pixel per second can be done using wplot

 Not as many as if you used bigger drawing commands, i.e. line 
drawing and stuff. Then its possible to draw a number of pixels with 
one write to memory instead of 1.
 
> Also, does anybody find that when windows programing that their memory
> drops like a sinking ship. Perhaps somebody has found this before and
> relised a way out of it or that they were doing something wrong as I mig=
ht
> be. But It seems that any program I do which runs on Workbench just sink=
s
> as the memory goes down like a countdown. Please help because it will be
> impossible to do anything in blitz if I cant solve this problem

 Ahh, but that happens anyway in Windows....oh you mean using windows 
on the Amiga. Sorry. There are a number of things you should check, 
but the culprit is most likely to be a high Workbench screen depth. 
Remember that when you open a window, you need to keep a copy of the 
window's bitmap and the area of the screen that it overlaps, so if 
you have a 256 colour WB then you're in trouble, especially for big 
windows.

 If the comments made about strings a couple of weeks ago are true 
(that the memory is not freed until the end of the program, when you 
change strings) then that may be another problem if you are doing a 
lot of string manipulation.

 You may also want to check that there is no memory leak caused by 
your code not freeing memory that it has allocated (may not be 
applicable to your program).

 If you are opening / closing a lot of windows or other objects and 
then not using them again, you could trying Free'ing them after you 
close them.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


@ENDNODE
