I've seen this before, it happened when I had a CD32 gamepad 
plugged in the joystick port, and a program window (made with 
Blitz) open.  Apparently it causes events continually.  I fixed it by 
calling FlushEvents, every now and again.  




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_183" "Re: gfx car programming"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 12 Oct 1998 18:46:14 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Mon, 12 Oct 1998 19:38:01 +0000
Subject: Re: gfx car programming

Hi,

> Does anybody know how many pixel per second can be done using wplot

It depends on many factors. If you're talking about gfx cards only then you
have to consider the CPU used, gfx card used, RTG software used (P96 or
CGFX), the screen mode used (8bit, 15bit, 16bit, 24bit...), the bus speed
available (Zorro2, Zorro3, CyberPPC, Ateo gfx etc..)

Despite all these factors you are still using the slowest method of
all to render your pixel because each WPlot will cause the OS
to check the RastPort of the window, calculate clips, layers etc..
an then finaly plot your chosen pixel.

So, you can still get well over 100,000 pixels per second but
don't expect wonders from an OS/RTG plot-pixel solution.

> Also, does anybody find that when windows programing that their
> memory drops like a sinking ship. Perhaps somebody has found this
> before and relised a way out of it or that they were doing something
> wrong as I might be.

Windows don't really use up much memory at all. It depends what
you mean by "drops like a sinking ship"... are you talking about
20k-100k or a few Meg? Depending on how many other windows
are open on your screen, window memory usage can be next to
nothing.

Cheers,

-- 
Paul Burkey <--> http://burkey.home.ml.org <-->



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_184" "Re: gfx car programming"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 12 Oct 1998 19:38:00 -0500
Subject: Re: gfx car programming

Hi Steven

On 12-Oct-98, Steven Dobbs wrote:

> Also, does anybody find that when windows programing that their memory drops
like a sinking ship. Perhaps somebody 
> has found this before and relised a way out of it or that they were doing
something wrong as I might be. But It seems that 
> any program I do which runs on Workbench just sinks as the memory goes down
like a countdown. Please help because it 
> will be impossible to do anything in blitz if I cant solve this problem

Well, opening a full-screen window on my 256 colour Workbench screen takes
only about 200k of memory.  It must be something else, unless you are opening
LOTS of large windows?

The WTitle command looses a bit of memory each time it is called, although
normally not enough to worry about.  But I have seen a program that used this
command to continously update the window titlebar to show the current cursor
x/y positions.  This would continously eat up memory.

Reloading to the same bitmap, shape, sound, or module # without Free'ing it
first will also use up memory.

These are just a few thoughts.  But once opened, a window itself won't use any
more memory...

