@NODE "Mail_214" "Re: GTMenu - Mutual exclude"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 26 Oct 1998 15:13:16 -0500
Subject: Re: GTMenu - Mutual exclude

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.


--BOUNDARY.1747505760.1

Hi Andre,

On 26-Oct-98, Andre Beer wrote:
> 
> Hi Luca,

> Thank you for the example. But please explain what is the system behind the
> mutual exclude flags? I want to use more than 5 items - how are the flags
for
> the sixth, seventh,... item?

For each menu item, you add one digit to the number.  So, for 10 items, you
have 10 places in the number.  All 1's except the current item, which is 0
(counting from the right end).  See the updated code attached.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1747505760.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="GTmutualX.asc"

GTMenuTitle 0,3,"MutualExclude2"
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,0,"These menus","",%1111111110
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,1,"are mutually","",%1111111101
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,2,"exclusive, ONE","",%1111111011
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,3,"of them MUST be","",%1111110111
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,4,"active","",%1111101111
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,5,"these items","",%1111011111
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,6,"will work","",%1110111111
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,7,"too and","",%1101111111
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,8,"probably as","",%1011111111
GTMenuItem 0,%001,3,9,"many as you want","",%0111111111

--BOUNDARY.1747505760.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_215" "Re: GTMenu - Mutual exclude"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 27 Oct 1998 05:41:49 -0500
Subject: Re: GTMenu - Mutual exclude

Hi,

On 26-Oct-98, Curt Esser wrote:

> On 26-Oct-98, Andre Beer wrote:
>> 
>> Hi Luca,
> 
>> Thank you for the example. But please explain what is the system behind the
>> mutual exclude flags? I want to use more than 5 items - how are the flags
> for
>> the sixth, seventh,... item?
> 
> For each menu item, you add one digit to the number.  So, for 10 items, you
> have 10 places in the number.  All 1's except the current item, which is 0
> (counting from the right end).  See the updated code attached.

I forgot to explain  ;)

When a menu item is selected, the flags you set for it are examined and all
items on the same menu (or submenu) that have a "1" will be de-selected.  Any
with a "0" are left alone.  So you always want the current item to have a "0",
but you could also set other items to "0" to not deselect them when this item
is selected.


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_216" "GTmenus question"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 21 Oct 1998 10:47:45 -0500
Subject: GTmenus question

Hi Everybody,

I am using GTmenus in my program in place of the standard menus.  These look
so much better!  But there is a problem:

With the old menus, I can use the "MenuState" command to disable menu items
that are not available.  This shows them ghosted, and the user can't select
them.

But the "GTMenuState" command does not do this  :(
It seems to only mark and unmark checkmarked menu items.

Is there a way to disable items in a GTmenu list?
Do I need to change the flags on my GTmenu, or am I doing something wrong?

Thanks for any help or examples...


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




