@NODE "Mail_235" "HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs."
Date: Sun, 11 Oct 1998 14:19:29 -0600 (CST)
From: "Ing. Carlos Villarroel Cortes" <carlosv@tac.unam.mx>
Subject: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs.

  This message is in MIME format.  The first part should be readable text,
  while the remaining parts are likely unreadable without MIME-aware tools.
  Send mail to mime@docserver.cac.washington.edu for more info.

---559023410-851401618-908137169=:22432

Please note that i will like to receive all my E-Mail at:
carlosv@cuk.redes.unam.mx
Sorry for the inconvenience.
---------------------------------------------------------
HELP! with the most needed Blitz Libraries.

Hello again to all blitzers out there!

The next are three libraries prospects that potentially can let us get the
last drop of power of any standard amiga (regardless of the CPU) that
doesn't have a graphics-card expansion (due economic or design reasons).
Mainly for games purposes (but never limited to).

- Virtual Blitter Library
- Virtual Bitmap Library
- C2P asyncronous Library

Next i'm going to explain every one:

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
VIRTUAL BLITTER LIBRARY:

The amiga graphic architecture was developed to run advanced video-games,
that is, a frame rate of about 50/60 Hz, or at least 25/30 Hz, the video
standards.  So the machine own an advanced display hardware, and two main
coprocesors: the Copper and the Blitter, apart from the CPU (not mentioning
the sprites and other extra hardware).  All of them can run concurrently in
full 'hardware multitasking' due the Direct Memory Access (DMA) to Chip Ram
properties that they all share. 

Under certain circunstances (all trying to access the chip ram) the DMA
could be saturated and the whole machine slows down.  But this is solved
easily by putting some Fast Ram in, this way the CPU can do all his
operations faster without interfere with the copprocesor's works.

Having said this (for the beginners out there, that is ;) -and considering
that today ALL the amigas have some fast ram- some of us are really annoyed
by the way that the acid blitter libraries work:  When you blit some thing
that need more than two colours -the most common case- THE CPU MUST WAIT!
until the blitter finish his work.  So this precious CPU time (the
difference between a good or crap A.I.  algorithm, between a good or crap
playability) is virtually trashed whithout any sensible reason.  More over
you need to reduce the frame rate mainly for this silly wait.

So actually there are different approaches to 'solve' this, but mainly some
of you -the ones with the fastest CPU's- simply forget the Blitter and use
custom CPUBlit routines.  The question again is:  Why we must waste a chip
that used properly could let us perfectioning the game playability with
more free CPU time??

The only and most sense way to make a game with full 50/60 hz frame rate is
simply by queueing all the blitter operations in every Vertical Blank
interruption, so by simply activating the blitter finish interrupt request
flag, the CPU can manage to order all the blits without any wait... sadly
the ACID SetInt library doesn't work with the blitter IRQ ( In fact, it
seems that this only work well with the Vertical Blank IRQ :( )

This way, we - Serge Veugelers and me - were trying to do something at
the respect. Finally we have managed the thing to work partially.

Attached to this mail is the last Serge's main code that does it with BLOCK
only type blits.  Unfortunately we must leave the project for a while
mainly due time limit projects, but -regardless of the CPU type: PPC or 68K
is a fact that a machine with a blitter copprocesor will work faster than
one without it! as you can see later down- THIS PROJECT MUST DO NOT WAIT ANY
MORE, why?  because with tools like this, the programmer can concentrate
more on the game itself rather than the technical things, and consecuently
the game will be of better quality, AND consecuently the amiga will have
more and better software, and... you can figure out the other reasons if
continue reading.

Is a fact that some day we will finish it, but maybe too much later...
so please, we need the HELP of the guru's out there that own experience
with machine code and that have already maked libraries for Blitz before.
The code only needs some things:  cookie cut blitting, proper library
conversion and maybe one or two optimizations (but this could work as it is
currently only adding the cookie instructions)

Please, i know some of you can do it in no-time ( Paul Burkey, this is
less than nothing compared to Foundation, and you can help the beginners
out  there  ; ).  We need more and better programs today's critic times and
providing the beginners with these tools could be a very good point.


VIRTUAL BITMAP LIBRARY:

Have you ever player Flash Back? did you know that this game could have a
big virtual screen with smooth scroll (50/60 hz) in a bare A500. Or maybe
you have played in the past a game called Syndicate? again did you know
that this could have a real smooth scroll and smoother blits (realistic
shadows included) for the small bobs?  Not to mention the lot of old (A500)
and recently (AGA) platformers, that moving a simply and alone sprite in the
screen, when reached some point the smooth scroll becomes jerky ...

All those programmers never realized that the Amiga can display a big
virtual screen WITHOUT the NEED OF REDRAW THE ENTIRE SCREEN EVERY FRAME.
How we can do it better?  you may ask...  well for a start i'm simply would
say that the only thing you need to redraw is the next column/row -or
column+row for diagonals- of the scroll map.

So this free all the rest of potentialy block blits to redraw the screen,
and we can use this precious time to blit more and better main characters.
But of course this does not come free, first you need the help (one line of
help in fact ;) of one of the copprocesors (no!, this time no blitter
stuff), the copper, but only for horizontal scroll, for vertical scroll the
hardware display is enough.  Second you need to reserve some more chip
memory (nothing compared to reserve a bigger than screen bitmap) and third,
( blitter stuff again ;) you need to maintain a special count for the blit
coords.  and do the appropiated clipped blits when needed.

Anyway it's a very small price to pay for a full 50/60 hz game.

This library will be the perfect complement for the first one.  So isometric
or platform style games will be easy and fast to do even in the oldest
amiga.  Next step will be to create a routine that will really maintain a
virtual map in memory of all the blocks/bobs and only draw those that must
appear in screen.  Really as if you have defined a super-big hardware
bitmap and simply scroll it by typing:  DisplayVBitmap n,x,y,... But this
isn't the important part, we must start with the first steps.

Any volunteers?  Good ML knowledge is required.  Attached is more info
- writted by Arno Hollosi - about this and some ML code to implement it.
The only thing that must be programmed is the blitter coords.  and clipping
stuff.  Again, any blitz programmer that ever need to do a big smooth
scroll will be very grateful.  Is a fact that the game genres mentioned
above will never pass out, and if amiga programmers can have more CPU to do
A.I.  antics this only could be better for all of us.  Please, some of you
can do it spending a small amount of time.


CHUNKY TO PLANAR ASYNCRONOUS LIBRARY:

Well it's nothing new that from some time ago the amigans (at least the
A1200 and lower users) had suffered when trying to do any decent 3D in
those machines, some have tried it with copper screens but this only leads
to blocky and small resolution screens, not to mention that a true AGA
palette isn't possible (these are 4096 ECS colours) and the CPU can't work
directly on the chipram for many reasons.  Thanks to god -and Jay Miner
too- we have another copprocesor that -AGAIN!- will help us: the blitter :/
( I'm sure now you will think twice before trying to underestimate it ;)
We can use it like a 'fake AKIKO'!?

Two years ago Juergen Fischer and the RIOT team have developed a novel
approach to the C2P problem, they have proved that we can use the blitter
to make the C2P conversion in paralell with the CPU, so the CPU is free to
render more complex routines while the blitter is making the time-consuming
work. Their routines are in full ML and have very little startup bugs (on
my A1200/030-50 they never crashed anyway) that could be solved by putting
the correct interruption bits at the exact time.

Attached to this mail is the original archive, i'm only would say that i
have tested some routines and it's possible to do a full screen 320x200,
256 colours, at 60 Hertz (for the NTSC one) with 1x1 pixels of course only
using the blitter and with little CPU overhead -almost nothing if the
chunky buffer is in ChipMem (slower, i think) and only one instruction in a
special jump/branch table format per chunky pixel if the buffer is in
FastMem-.  In fact, nothing compared with standard C2P routines.  (So we
can have game conversions like TombRaider or a new version of AlienBreed 3D
running in any A1200/030 at full 50 Hz :)

Of course, to manage this standar resolution -320 pixels wide- at that
frame rate we must pay with a small and unnoticeable flicker but this
another history, first we need the library working at 196x256 in full
screen (50/60 Hz).  ( Paul West this one is for you, your library can grow
and turning in the best and definitive C2P Amiga Blitz lib!  - but first
please purchase the Video Backup System and make a backup of your HD in a
VHS VCR every month!  :) - In fact before buying a ZIP drive i have tested
the VBS and it's pretty reliable, a must for all amigans that doesn't own
an SCSI interface and don't want to turn into disk jockeys - )
---------------------------------------------------------------------------


So far, what do you think of this?  The only true thing is that with a PPC
or not, the hardware is still here and it's the only amiga standard, more
over, a program that doesn't use the blitter for example, never will be
faster that one that does use it.  And it's time to prove what the amiga
can do it better and faster than the other machines!  After all you have
buyed an amiga mainly due it's default graphic architecture!  I really want
to see some of you proving that any chunky graphics card can do a virtual
bitmap scroll faster and bigger than the actual amiga AGA hardware can do!

Anyway the routines are almost done, the algorithms can be converted to PPC
or any other processor without major hassle so a PPC library could compile
any 68k Blitz game...

After all the best way to approach the future is doing the better
at present!

Thanks in advance and keep up the good work.

Carlos Villarroel

For any questions please write to: carlosv@cuk.redes.unam.mx

Actual project: 

Scala Patch
-----------
Not all in Blitz (some c/asm) but yes!  this will do anything -asyncronous
60/50 Hz video effects- that scala can't and will be controlled directly by
any scala script.  Realtime-bitmap-effect sources are welcome, in special
fast zoom-in/out routines.


