@NODE "Mail_237" "Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 12 Oct 1998 18:29:03 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 12 Oct 98 16:02:29 +0000
Subject: Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs.
Encoding: 7bit

Carlos,

> CHUNKY TO PLANAR ASYNCRONOUS LIBRARY:
 
> Two years ago Juergen Fischer and the RIOT team have developed a novel
> approach to the C2P problem, they have proved that we can use the blitter
> to make the C2P conversion in paralell with the CPU, so the CPU is free to
> render more complex routines while the blitter is making the time-consuming
> work. Their routines are in full ML and have very little startup bugs (on
> my A1200/030-50 they never crashed anyway) that could be solved by putting
> the correct interruption bits at the exact time.

> Of course, to manage this standar resolution -320 pixels wide- at that
> frame rate we must pay with a small and unnoticeable flicker but this
> another history, first we need the library working at 196x256 in full
> screen (50/60 Hz).  ( Paul West this one is for you, your library can grow
> and turning in the best and definitive C2P Amiga Blitz lib!

I've looked at the asynchronous thing. I was sceptical and with due
cause because I know that blitter is not capable of tremendous speed
compared with modern cpu's.

First of all the main thing is that the blitter-screens are 2x1 or 2x2
pixels, not 1x1, so getting so excited about it running at such a high
framerate is hardly surprising. Also the system is targetted at the
low-end, not high-end cpu's. It even sais that an 030/50 is likely
better off with a cpu-based c2p. It will give good results on low end
030's and 020's but not that many people have unexpanded Amiga's
anyway and a 2x2 mode isn't very attractive.

The reason I didn't convert any blitter-assisted c2p's into my
collection was simply because they are mainly aimed at much lower cpu-
horesepower machines. It is true that much time can be gained from
performing asynchronous blitter conversion and there are normal 1x1
c2p's which claim to work at about 60fps or so on an 040/25 using the
blitter to do a few stages of the conversion. Getting those dam things
to work though is another matter entirely. I sure as hell couldn't,
and for anything from an 040/40 upwards there is no point anyway. It
might be true that an regardless of the cpu power you will gain some
time by having at least part of the conversion running asynchronously
with the blitter, and yes it is very `amiga' to make use of the lovely
custom hardware, but the benefits in the high end are so negligible
that there isn't much point, and you don't /have/ to attain the
absolutely maximum possible speed all the time. There are other things
to think of.

I'm not going to be converting the blitter-based c2p or any other
blitter assisted c2p's or any 2x1 or 2x2 c2p's, mainly because I don't
need to or want to. The things that I work on in blitz in my own
projects are sometimes useable by other people. The selection of
chunky to planar routines only came about because I myself needed them
and the same applies to the screenmode hook thing and other code I've
released. I haven't personally got the time or inclination to code all
these things with no personal interest in it myself. If I'm not going
to enjoy it myself then it can make programming incredibly boring.
There are plenty of other people that could convert the blitter c2p
thing for use in blitz if they wanted to.

Your properly queud blit routines are interesting, the concept at
least, as I noticed also that it wasn't really a proper queue because
you had to wait till it'd finished before you could do anything else.
Thumbs up for that one. I just don't think there is much future in
blitter-based chunky screens.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
