@NODE "Mail_239" "Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 Wed, 14 Oct 1998 12:51:24 -0600 (CST)
Date: Wed, 14 Oct 1998 12:51:24 -0600 (CST)
From: Carlos Villarroel Cortes <carlosv@redes.unam.mx>
Subject: Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs.

Thanks to Anton and Rui for his comments.

First of all, i'm very sad by the lack of interest from the most advanced
users/programmers out there.  It seems that none of you (except Paul West)
want a blitz routine that will let your games run at full 50/60 Hz in full
multitasking if needed.  The work isn't very hard really and we all can be
benefited from it. Maybe it's my bad english the cause, so i will try
to explain some additional things:


- BLITZ MODE ISN'T DEAD:

Before i go further i will say that Blitz mode isn't dead because there is
a little trick that can let us use the blitz-mode commands in full
multitasking, - as long as you don't want run it in a fake amiga/emulator
with a chunky graphics card only -.  I have tested this intensively and
works fine.

So, interruptions - initiated in a system friendly way -, copper lists and
the other blitz mode related stuff is completely usable while you can
render in background.  Of course if you want all the speed of the CPU you
can use the standard BLITZ mode and turn off the S.O. indeed.

You may ask:  Initiated in a system friendly way??.  Yes, that's what the
code i have send you does ( VirtualBlitter Library ).  So all these three
libraries can let us run games at 50/60 Hz in full multitasking, while the
CPU receives/send data using the serial port or process an image in
background.


- BLITTER/DISPLAY-HARDWARE COMMANDS CAN WORK IN MULTITASKING:

At 50/60 Hz in full multitasking??  Yes, and with smooth bob movements too.
How?  well again, the blitter is the response.  It can do all the drawing
stuff while the CPU is free, again that's what does the code i have already
send ( VBlit Lib ). Note that the ACID BLITTER COMMANDS CAN'T DO IT and
they are bugged too!


- AMIGA HARDWARE CAN DISPLAY A BLOCK BASED MAP OF "ANY" SIZE
  AT 50/60 Hz WITHOUT THE NEED TO REDRAW THE ENTIRE SCREEN EVERY FRAME.

This is related to the Virtual BitMap Library.  Horizontal size limited by
chipram.  But you can have easily more than 640 SCREENS to say something.
Vertical size is unlimited.  

You need only to blit the next column/row.  The blitter is more than
capable of this, also this will let us use the blitter to draw the main
bobs.  All this with the CPU almost FREE.  Again that's very close related
to the VBLit Lib routine i have send.

To make the virtual bitmap library work we need to follow a certainly
coordinates/clipping stuff that I CAN EXPLAIN IN DETAIL IF SOME OF YOU ARE
INTERESTED.  This way the ones that doesn't know how to program in ASM, CAN
DO it IN BASIC or PSEUDOCODE.  Then some one with good ML knowledge can
translate it to make a fully functional library.  YOU CAN HELP EVEN IF YOU
DON'T KNOW ANYTHING ABOUT AMIGA HARDWARE PROGRAMMING OR ASM!!  The
important part is the basic algorithm, that must be the fastest way to do
it.

Some time ago i have heard in a IRC channel a guy that said:  Blitz-List?
lamer-list! more like...  I'm sure that we can prove he was wrong.


- BLITTER ASSISTED C2P COULD BE USEFUL AND NOT TOO HARD TO CODE.

My response to Paul could be more explicative:

On: 12 Oct 98 16:02:29, Paul West typed:

>Carlos,

>I've looked at the asynchronous thing. I was sceptical and with due
>cause because I know that blitter is not capable of tremendous speed
>compared with modern cpu's.

That's ok, the blitter can match the speed of a 020, but not more.

>First of all the main thing is that the blitter-screens are 2x1 or 2x2
>pixels, not 1x1, so getting so excited about it running at such a high
>framerate is hardly surprising. 

I agree, but also i have mentioned a special trick (with aga sprites) that
can let us have 320 pixels wide screens with some minimal flicker at 60 Hz.
Anyway we can have also real 30/25 Hz screens with full 320x200 (1x1)
screens.  And if we need full 60Hz at higher resolutions the blitter still
can do one part of the whole process.

>Also the system is targetted at the
>low-end, not high-end cpu's. It even sais that an 030/50 is likely
>better off with a cpu-based c2p. 

It's true, but the CPU will waste some precious time.

>It will give good results on low end
>030's and 020's but not that many people have unexpanded Amiga's
>anyway and a 2x2 mode isn't very attractive.

For the ones without graphics cards, 2x2 could be very good. And AGA
colours can produce some pretty results.

>The reason I didn't convert any blitter-assisted c2p's into my
>collection was simply because they are mainly aimed at much lower cpu-
>horesepower machines. It is true that much time can be gained from
>performing asynchronous blitter conversion and there are normal 1x1
>c2p's which claim to work at about 60fps or so on an 040/25 using the
>blitter to do a few stages of the conversion. Getting those dam things
>to work though is another matter entirely. I sure as hell couldn't,
>and for anything from an 040/40 upwards there is no point anyway. It
>might be true that an regardless of the cpu power you will gain some
>time by having at least part of the conversion running asynchronously
>with the blitter, and yes it is very `amiga' to make use of the lovely
>custom hardware, but the benefits in the high end are so negligible
>that there isn't much point,

It wouldn't be much point if the work to do is too hard, but this case,
isn't, specially for some one with experience in C2P stuff.  Please read
the rest of this mail for a better explain.  (The IMPORTANT part)

>and you don't /have/ to attain the
>absolutely maximum possible speed all the time. There are other things
>to think of.

We can think in multitasking for example, the speed of a 020 can be the
difference between a full 60/50 Hz game in multitasking and other that must
turn off the system to gain full speed.

>I'm not going to be converting the blitter-based c2p or any other
>blitter assisted c2p's or any 2x1 or 2x2 c2p's, mainly because I don't
>need to or want to.

Yes, when i have a 4000 with Cybergraphics :), i will think the same.  But
anyway when you release something, it's better do it compatible at least
with all AGA amigas.

>The things that I work on in blitz in my own
>projects are sometimes useable by other people. The selection of
>chunky to planar routines only came about because I myself needed them
>and the same applies to the screenmode hook thing and other code I've
>released. I haven't personally got the time or inclination to code all
>these things with no personal interest in it myself. If I'm not going
>to enjoy it myself then it can make programming incredibly boring.

Again, i agree with you.

>There are plenty of other people that could convert the blitter c2p
>thing for use in blitz if they wanted to.

I'm expect this, and also waiting (while working :) for one or more
volunteers. 

>Your properly queud blit routines are interesting, the concept at
>least, as I noticed also that it wasn't really a proper queue because
>you had to wait till it'd finished before you could do anything else.

Thats true!, and it MUST be so. Why? because when you are making a full
50/60 Hz game you must be sure that ALL the blits can be done in a single
frame (if you don't want some jerky movements) so you must try first the
most demanding case to find out the adecuated frame rate.  (30/25 or 50/60
Hz) Also a properly queue will take more CPU cycles that we don't need to
waste!

---- IMPORTANT ----

If you already have take a look to the Blitter C2P asynchronous routines
please note that maybe the trickiest bit is the startup code (for the blit
interruptions and related stuff that doesn't need to be in full machine
language as maximum speed is not needed for this), and the queue setup for
the blitter instructions, thats what does in fact the VBlitter library code
i have send.  The rest it's only related to setup the correct Vertical
Blank interruption that must order all the blits; block-blit or C2P stuff:)
(this can be done in blitz without worries).

So the only real work here is to figure out the best blitter command
sequence to make the faster C2P conversion.  And then throw'em in the blitz
queue every frame.  ( Maybe when some of you have some spare time, can take
a fast look to the source of the asynchronous stuff to find it :)

>Thumbs up for that one. 

Thank Paul, and please: Can you help converting the queue blit function to
ASM and check for one or two optimizations?

Any volunteer to make the cookie part?  This can be done in no-time
specially by those of you who already have maked CPUBlit related commands.
(Hey Rui!  you must know some of them as you page contains these sort of
routines)

I think those blit routines can be the most useful thing to improve our
scroll-type games.

>I just don't think there is much future in
>blitter-based chunky screens.

Yours is a very respectable opinion. If not much, maybe some future? :)

Anyway we all think the first two libs. are valuable indeed.
Or i'm wrong?

Thanks to all you for reading.

For any questions please e-mail me:

Carlos Villarroel
carlosv@cuk.redes.unam.mx




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_240" "RE: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs."
From: "Wright J.A" <J.A.Wright@rhbnc.ac.uk>
Subject: RE: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs.
Date: Wed, 14 Oct 1998 21:41:56 +0100

ok,
     to be honest... i can`t stand having OS friendly games.....  i like
just dumping the OS so i can get on with using ALL the resources available
100%...   talkong of the blitter also......  you said that the Blitz blit
commands don`t use the Blitter in parallel with the CPU, which actually
isn`t true....  when you do a Blit the Blitter frees the CPU just before it
starts drawing the last bitplane of the blit....  this is quite a logical
thing to do really bcos if you free`d the CPU at the very start of the Blit
the Blitter would then have to wait for the CPU to tell it which bitplanes
to blit next.... 

anyway, i`ve never coded a game that has run too slow or dropped below
frame rate.... and i can`t believe some ppl seem to have such slow stuff...


oh well,
laters,
James


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_241" "Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 14 Oct 1998 21:51:45 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
