I don't see why. Normal cpu-only c2p's are compatible with all AGA
amiga's. Where do you want to draw the line?
 
> Thats true!, and it MUST be so. Why? because when you are making a full
> 50/60 Hz game you must be sure that ALL the blits can be done in a single
> frame (if you don't want some jerky movements)

I think a lot of people have given up on doing things in 1 frame these
days mainly because you can't get /enough/ done in 1 frame. In most
cases anyway. You can do platform games and such quite well in chipram
methods fairly efficiently but again there is a limit to how much you
can do. Yes, it is true that c2p is generally aimed at 25/30fps rather
than 50/60 but you can get a lot more done in that time.

> If you already have take a look to the Blitter C2P asynchronous routines

I took a look.

> So the only real work here is to figure out the best blitter command
> sequence to make the faster C2P conversion.  And then throw'em in the blitz
> queue every frame.  ( Maybe when some of you have some spare time, can take
> a fast look to the source of the asynchronous stuff to find it :)

I have no idea how blitz handles its blitting.
 
> Thank Paul, and please: Can you help converting the queue blit function to
> ASM and check for one or two optimizations?

No, sorry. I said it's a good thing but I have too many projects on
the go already. I am not interested in working with the hardware
blitter of the AGA chipset anymore. It isn't suited to the kind of
things I am intending to do. I might at some stage soon take a look at
a blitter-assisted c2p again to see if I can get it working, but I am
not interested in these copper, blitter, or sprite screens. TBH I
thought that this kind of hardware bashing went out with the A500.
 
> >I just don't think there is much future in
> >blitter-based chunky screens.

I don't know. For somebody somewhere it might have a use but it will
only be a minority thing and what with the shift to graphics cards,
c2p routines of any kind aren't going to live much longer.

-- 
Paul.

