Hi,

>> not interested in these copper, blitter, or sprite screens. TBH I
>> thought that this kind of hardware bashing went out with the A500.

> I don=B4t think so, common sense says that we must left blitz and try =

> C++/Java because they're going to work on al future CPU's/Machines. But=
 =

> we -the amigans- are not so common. And the "hardware bashing" is what =

> makes a machine like the Amiga so special. =


This kind of hardware bashing just isn't viable if you're thinking of wri=
ting
a game that will be accepted by the majoraty of users. Whether you like i=
t
or not most "active" Amiga users have gfx cards and 040+ nowadays.
What I mean by active is users who are still buying the latest games and
moving into areas of computing like the Internet. You understand that the=

Amigas custom hardware is very special, so you will realise that gfx-card=
s
can't do most of the things that AGA can. This means that any game
written in such a way as to utilize these special powers will require
huge changes to run on RTG systems or maybe RTG is droped altogether.
If you're not interested in the commercial success of a project then
please feel free to ignore all this...

> Not all the amigans can afford the money to buy a tower/graphics card. =

> Most think that a faster processor is more productive. After all, the =

> Amiga hardware display is anything but obsolete.

The Amigas hardware display has been dropped by all major game
developers. Name one Amiga game that has been released in the last
two years (Since Worms) that actually *uses* the Amigas hardware
and does it in a way that makes gfx-cards look unnecessary. =


I write this message with regret that I ever used the Amigas hardware
for Foundation. I wish I'd done the whole thing in a chunky buffer with
optimized Asm rendering. That way the majority of Foundations users
(gfx card/040+ users) would be playing a game that is 2-3 times as fast
and smooth and the rest would have something to look forward to
when they upgraded. Instead of that, I get about 10 emails a week from
people upgrading from AGA to gfx-card complaining that the speed
isn't much better. Damn AGA, dragging me down! ;) So thats why I'm
working on a major rewrite which could lead to a new release of the
game next year. If that happens you can be sure that the Blitter will
not get so much as a sniff of my graphics :)

Of course, if you're interested in writing games for non-commercial
purposes then I have great respect for the hard work that goes into
programming AGA hardware to give optimum results. I'm a great fan
of he Amigas 'demo scene' and I'm always impressed by the effects
that can be achieved... However, almost all of todays 'AGA Demo's'
are based around chunky buffer rendering and optimized c2p so
even thats a bad example of AGA at it's best. =


Cheers,

-- =

<- Paul Burkey <-> http://burkey.home.ml.org ->



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_246" "Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 15 Oct 1998 15:27:36 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 15 Oct 98 15:00:15 +0000
Subject: Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs.
Encoding: 8bit

Carlos,

> I understand, that's the reason what i'm searching for help.
> Any volunteer?? Maybe some of you that are in process to make a new game?

What I personally am doing at the moment is a game which has one or
two superbitmaps in fastram. c2p is performed directly from a window
on the superbitmap to the chipram display. The way I can see the
blitter helping with this is in the c2p, not in the scroll method.
There is no way I can work with a chipram-based tile scroller because
the land in my tanks game is large and the game environment even
larger, it just wont fit into chipram especially as working in chipram
means you have to have a doublebuffer. So a chipram superbitmap is no
good and trying to do it with a chipram tile-method isn't viable
because it massively complicates the handling of the environment. I
have a huge land graphic which cannot be made of tiles and has to be
permanently alterable in its entirity. Even if I stored it as tiles it
wouldn't work very well because it would make the animation and stuff
so incredibly complicated. There is development time to think of.
  
> Hope you do it ASAP and sure you can get it working.

Well I might have a look this afternoon. I would like to speed up the
c2p if possible because even though it's fast I would still like it
faster. It just depends on if I can get the blitter code to work as
it's all in assembler, has to be converted somewhat to work in blitz,
and I'm not sure if it's system friendly or meant to work without
multitasking.
 
> > thought that this kind of hardware bashing went out with the A500.
> 
> I don´t think so, common sense says that we must left blitz and try 
> C++/Java because they're going to work on al future CPU's/Machines. But 
> we -the amigans- are not so common. And the "hardware bashing" is what 
> makes a machine like the Amiga so special.

Well for one thing working in Amiga mode, which is my choice, doesn't
very easily allow you to do copperlists or hardware sprites. Yes it's
possible and I've done it before but it isn't exactly simple and who
is going to write a game that relies on hardware sprites when they
wont work on graphics cards. It means more code. So the way for me at
least is to have a system that is almost exactly the same for graphics
cards as for AGA and that means there can only be blitter usage (if
possible) in the c2p.
 
> Not all the amigans can afford the money to buy a tower/graphics card. 

Me either.

> Most think that a faster processor is more productive. After all, the 
> Amiga hardware display is anything but obsolete. 
> Some ones are saying it's slow, i say it's badly programmed.

Well, it just depends on what you want to do. If you really do want a
lot of objects moving about the amount is going to be limited by
chipram access speeds, and freeing up the cpu by way of a queue isn't
going to mean that it is possible to then blit more things to chipram
because there isn't any available time. You can only use the spare cpu
time for processing of the game, handling variables and such. Also if
you push chipram usage to its limits by having larger displays and
resolutions then you have radically less time for c2p. Sure a nice
superbitmap or such in chipram would be nice and smooth in hires, but
like I say it isn't feasible at any size, and doing it with tiles is
only possible so long as you are writing a game that allows it. The
way my game works it's almost like a paint program in that the picture
has to be permanently stored in its entirity.

I may look into the blitter assisted c2p's this afternoon. Maybe I can
figure it out now that I am much more familiar with the structure of
the routines.

-- 
Paul.

