From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Thu, 15 Oct 1998 16:54:45 +0000
Subject: Re: HELP! Most wanted Blitz Libs.

Hi,

>> people upgrading from AGA to gfx-card complaining that the speed
>> isn't much better. Damn AGA, dragging me down! ;)

> I was just about to ask "why don't you convert it to chunky then?",
> when you went on to say...

It was too big a job to do at the time and I prefer to spend time on
gamplay rather than graphics speed. Now the gameplay is working
well I can see how necessary the chunky rewrite was. Another
problem was the "slow cpu + AGA" market was still quite healthy
a year ago so it wasn't easy to ignore it. A year later and the move
to RTG has been huge. This time next year AGA will be ready to be
forgotten which will be great!

>> which could lead to a new release of the
>> game next year. If that happens you can be sure that the Blitter will
>> not get so much as a sniff of my graphics :)

> Except maybe in the c2p ;)

yeah, I guess so. <grumble grumble> ;)

> I think AGA is becoming more of just a normal display device, as would
> be a graphics card, rather than the additional features such as
> blitter, sprites, and copperlist effects.

so much more can now be done in chunky mode such as transparancies,
texture mapping, bitmap rotations, real-time lighting/shading etc.. Stuff
like blitting and sprites are all easily done in chunky mode together
with a mixture of the effects I just listed. Using the blitter only allows you
to displaying pre-rendered graphics while the chunky mode allows
you to change things in real-time. This is the kind of thing people want
to see in games and it does give the game designer more space for
creativity. I hate to keep going on about high-res displays, large gfx
bandwidth, fancy effects etc.. I know you can make good games in lowres
screens without all that fancy stuff but if people can get good games *and*
fancy graphics then thats what they will choose. There's plenty of very
good games with very good graphics out there.

Cheers,

-- 
<- Paul Burkey <-> http://burkey.home.ml.org ->



