> > this is quite a
> > logical
> > > thing to do really bcos if you free`d the CPU at the very start of th=
e
> > Blit
> > > the Blitter would then have to wait for the CPU to tell it which
> > bitplanes
> > > to blit next....

The last thing is more logical in fact, blitter must wait the CPU orders if=
=20
you want to explote the full CPU speed. Anyway this also doesn=B4t do the m=
ost=20
optimal thing. (seems that you haven=B4t read my first mail)
=20
> >=20
> > I don't see why you can't just open an interleaved bitmap and cludge
> > on a bitmap in 1 bitplane 8 times the height, and the same with
> > shapes, so that all blits require only one cpu instance for all
> > bitplanes.
> >=20
> >=20
> hehe.. i don`t see why not either.... but i just never tried it.....  8)
>=20

It=B4s true, but how about cookie-cut blitting? you are going to need a=20
cookie-cut image with the same size of your main shape (wasting a=20
lot of chip ram). Anyway, again, it=B4s not the best way to do blitting stu=
ff.
Why? simply because you never will know when the blitter finish, unless=20
you use the Blitter Finish Interruption. That=B4s what the Virtual Blitter=
=20
Library code does.


@ENDNODE
