Encoding: 7bit

Hi.

Attatched to this message is a fairly small archive containing an
executable demo program, demonstrating interlaced chunky to planar in
operation. If you haven't got AGA access, but have a graphics card,
the row-lacing will work because I've also added that feature when
there's gfx card output (untested!)

The program is an IFF pic viewer of sorts, working in fastram and
using c2p for display. It will reject Ham images or anything with more
than 8 bitplanes (sorry, my custom ILBM-to-chunky loader).

You select a screenmode that you want. If there isn't enough memory to
open that screen in 256 colours, *double buffered*, the program will
just end. The dimensions will be cropped to the nearest 64 pixels
horizontally and the nearest 2 pixels vertically, if in AGA. If in
graphics-card screens the horizontal is clipped to the nearest 32
pixels. The 64-pixel limitation is due to fetchmodes working properly
but also to let the column-interlacing work.

The file you chose in the asl requester will be then loaded in
and you can browse it by moving the mouse around the display area. It
will be updated realtime from fastram using c2p.

There are two types of interlacing possible: rows and columns. The row
lace method is like normal interlace. It doesn't look too bad but if
you move around in circles you'd think you were having hallucinations.
The colum method is more solid but fast movements don't look very
coherent. Currently in the demo program attatched BOTH methods are
being used simultaneously. It's really fun, I promise you!

So, effectively the routine will be only converting 1/4 of the screen
each frame. It'll therefore report stupidly high framerates when you
press the mousebutton to exit. ;-)

Let me know what you think? If you want, I'll also post versions that
show only one type of lacing at a time, rows or columns. They both
have some drawbacks. Neither is perfect. But what it does mean is that
you can do twice as much stuff in your main loop per frame. True you
only get to see half (or quarter!) of it in the next c2p update, but
it's not a bad little feature if you want it. It might be suited to
certain types of displays better than others. Maybe it'd do well for
3D.

Somehow it seems that the two lacing methods working simultaneously
kind of helps to disguise each other. The row-lacing breaks up the
effect of the column lacing and vice versa.

NB: I think the fps readings may only be accurate for PAL 50Hz
displays because the routine relies on the number 50 as part of the
calculation.

Apart from wobbling around the place like a dream it's not bad! :-)
In this demo it takes 4 frames before a full screen is drawn. Also
note that you can load any size pictures (even really huge ones) so
long as they will fit into fastram (largest block?). If you haven't
got any fastram then, well, why the hell not? <g>

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk







