Encoding: 7bit

Hi.

Attatched is an archive containing sourcecode for a full
interlace-capable chunky-to-planar system. There are loads of
variables to play with at the start of the program. You can see for
yourself that it doesn't look terribly nice doing interlaced c2p for
2d stuff, although it might have some 3d uses. Also you have to note
that using an interlace method in an effort to have more objects will
effectively halve the refresh-framerate. You don't get anything for
free with this, it's just a rearrangement of priorities. In PAL Lores
the update is fast enough to be quite acceptable.

Also in the archive is an executable of the fastram ILBM viewer, which
will now load Ham8 images (but Ham6 will be wrong) as well as normal
colourmapped ILBMs. As I said, using this in PAL Lores works very
well, but larger dimensions and more demands on chipram slow down
the conersion and it doesn't look very nice when that happens. There
is now right-mousebutton functionality to toggle between the different
interlace types. There are four modes altogether. It starts in normal
`solid' c2p mode. A single RMB click will put it into row lacing mode.
A second click will take you to column lacing mode, and a third click
will take you to both lace modes simultaneously. Leftmousebutton exits
and reports the framerate for the current c2p mode you're using, not
the entire duration of the viewing.

Some of the demo code in the c2p tester could be better but the
statements containing assembler are the main things you'll need if you
want to use the system yourself. The c2p itself will autodetect
your CPU for 030 or 040 routines and the routines are generally as
flexible as they can be (ie almost unlimited size, source and dest
modulos for `windows'. Double buffering is demonstrated, although
it's slightly tricky when doing both lace methods at the same time.

You can of course use the c2p without lacing if you want. I think
lacing might be useful for 3d such as a doom/quake type game. It
helps immensely when there isn't too much contrast on the screen. The
nice feature of the 3d situation is that when you are not moving you
get a full 1x1 pixel display, which would not be the case with 2x1,
2x2 and other pixel-economising methods (ooh big words!). It is only
when the player moves that the display alters. Possibly row-lacing
would be best for most of those games where pivoting is around the
verticle axis as long-distance horizontal movements don't hold too
well in column-lacing.

You also have to remember that if you use the time saved by
interlacing for doing additional processing, you drop the effective
framerate and you can notice this. It is probably best used to
effectively raise your apparent framerate than to double the amount of
processing, and in a 3d situation you'd probably want to be doing
twice as much processing unless you could write an interlaced render
routine. The same applies for any other work you want to do such as 2d
blits. If you can work out an interlaced blit routine (not necessarily
double buffered) you could indeed gain some time. Basically, if you
don't halve the amount of processing you do each frame (by way of
doing every other line) then you stand to make only a loss with this.
But indeed for a nice 3d game that renders usually in `scanlines' or
whatever, processing only half the amount of lines and using an
interlaced c2p should either double the framerate or double the amount
of work you can do at the same framerate.

It might even be a routine without any real application, who knows.

Any probs let me know. I challenge someone to come up with a decent
use for it.


-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk









