@NODE "Mail_277" "Re: interlaced c2p"
 with ESMTP id <0F10001N7KGOJA@hermes.ucd.ie> for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie;
 Sun, 18 Oct 1998 09:19:39 +0100 (BST)
 <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Sun, 18 Oct 1998 19:50:43 +1300
Date: Sun, 18 Oct 1998 20:51:00 +1200
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Subject: Re: interlaced c2p

On 16-Oct-98, Paul wrote:
 
>I've done a test with interlaced c2p. Hmm. Well, as you might expect
>you get to double the number of objects you can do. Either that or you
>double your framerate. For example, 90 32x32 objects at 50fps,
>320x200 on an 040/25. However, it doesn't look too pretty.

  How many objects do you get with a normal 320x200 screen running at
25fps? I would assume a normal screen at 25fps would effectively run at
the same speed as an interlaced 50fps screen, or is there a performance
increase by using interlace? 

  Just interested- Anton :-)
 
-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz> ICQ #15349462 
   



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_278" "Re: interlaced c2p"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 19 Oct 1998 18:57:11 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 19 Oct 98 15:19:54 +0000
Subject: Re: interlaced c2p
Encoding: 7bit

>   How many objects do you get with a normal 320x200 screen running at
> 25fps? I would assume a normal screen at 25fps would effectively run at
> the same speed as an interlaced 50fps screen, or is there a performance
> increase by using interlace? 

There is no performance increase from using interlaved, all you're
doing it prioritising object rendering over chunky to planar
conversion, so you have twice as much time to do objects but the
screen takes two game loops to fully update, so is an effective
halving of the update.

With a normal 320x200 c2p the framerate is about 50fps on an 040/25 or
thereabouts. I got 55fps once.

On an 040/25, the results are as follows for 320x200:

1110 8x8 masked objects
1580 8x8 unmasked objects
380 16x16 masked objects
580 16x16 unmasked objects
110 32x32 masked objects
185 32x32 unmasked objects
25  64x64 masked objects
42  64x64 unmasked objects

The thing to bear in mind is that I do not make seperate statement
calls for each object. I have a single statement in which a movement
table is handled. Each object is bounced around the screen, and the
table requires 6 bytes read and written per object. The objects are
rendered from the table inside the same statement, so this is somewhat
hardcoded. Also increasing the screen size will have quite an effect
on the number of objects. For example, 320x240 yields 75 32x32 masked
objects as opposed to the 110 that you get at 320x200. Also there is
no background preservation, restoration, clearscreen, game processing
or anything else going on (including multitasking).

The 64x64 results suggest that an area of 320x540 unmasked can be
blitted per frame. The 32x32 results suggest an area of 320x590. The
16x16 results suggest an area of 320x460 can be blitted. I think the
32x32 results are higher due to the smaller widths probably meaning
more efficient copyback cache usage, whereas after that the 16x16
object amount is less because there is more memory access required in
the movement table for that many objects. The 8x8 results suggest an
area of 320x320, for example. Bigger objects are slightly more
favoured because there is less additional memory needed to store and
handle movement and positions.

Like I said earlier there is no performance gain from using interlace.
You aren't suddenly getting extra processing time for nothing. To be
doing less chunky to planar work for each loop means the effective
framerate is halved, or given the appearance of doubling. The
row-interlacing makes it look like the routine runs at 50fps, but it
is only half of the screen that is running at that speed. It takes two
loops in order to do the whole screen, so is still basically 25fps. If
you were to use the time `saved' by interlacing to draw twice as many
objects, the overall framerate of a full screen refresh would halve to
16fps or something like that.

Also note that with an 060/50 you generally get double the
performance of the overall loop (twice as many objects).
-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
