@NODE "Mail_280" "Re: Interleaved chunky"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Fri, 2 Oct 1998 18:45:08 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 2 Oct 98 19:36:35 +0000
Subject: Re: Interleaved chunky
Encoding: 7bit

Krzysiek Jonko,

> I wonder if anybody have WORKING chunky functions on interleaved
> screen? All libraries I seen can't do that...
> Most important for me is ChunkyToBitmap function

I wondered how long it'd be before somebody asked for this.

Normally chunky-to-planar converters have a few ground rules that you
have to adhere to. It's part of the way they are designed for optimum
speed.

First of all bitmap memory (the data for the graphics) has to be
contiguous memory. So you can't just create a bitmap object, you have
to first reserve some chip memory with something like InitBank
0,320*256,$10002. Then you use something like CludgeBitmap
0,320,256,8,Bank(0).

Once this is done you can begin to convert data to planar. Now, you
talk of interleaved chunky. It is not normal or necessary or even
possible to have an interleaved chunky /source/, because you can only
interleve bitplanes (which chunky doesn't have). You can have
interleaved planar bitmaps however. It adds a little to the complexity
of the chunky to planar routine. First and foremost the chunky to
planar routine has to be able to work on a line-by-line basis, so has
to support a horizontal modulo. I have already done this. At the end
of each converted line of pixels, the routine has to then take the
modulo from the blitz bitmap object and add it to the output address.

Additionally, however, the data for the c2p has to be set up
differently. You have to tell it how many bytes there are in a
bitplane. It uses this as an offset multiplier to output longwords to
selected bitplanes. Instead of this being the size of a bitplane in
bytes, to make it work for interleaved you have to make it the number
of bytes in one line (ebwidth). Then, once all the bitplanes for a
single line have been output, an skip value has to be added to the
output address, the value of which is ebwidth*(planes-1), or in other
words enough to skip from the end of one line in the first bitplane to
the start of the first line of the first bitplane on the next line.
It sounds confusing. Alterations also have to be made to the c2p
routine itself because it will have to check a different value in
trying to determine wether the operation is complete or not. It
normally does this by comparing the current output address with the
address off the end of the first bitplane. This will of course have to
be altered for interleaved usage by multiplying the value by the
number of bitplanes before addition.

No joke! It's quite a complicated set of modifications.

I think that after all that it would probably output correctly to an
interleaved bitmap. However, further alterations would have to be made
to the initialisation routine in order to output the correct values
for interleaved bitmaps, or to make it so that it relies upon a
bitmap's ebwidth in order to function transparently for either
interleaved or non-interleaved bitmaps.

I have to tell you this though, there is absolutely no gain in
outputting chunky data to an interleaved display. In fact, even more
work has to be done than is normally so. Not just work to make the
thing operate properly in the first place, but extra work during the
running of the conversion routine. There is no feasible reason why you
would want an interlaved planar display when using chunky to planar,
because ALL graphics operations are to be done in chunky and then
converted. If you are intending to mix the chunky output with planar
blits, blitter operations, or other bitplane-based things then you're
moving into the territory of complicated modifications. This is not to
say it is impossible, it is just a bit longwinded.

Interleaved bitmaps only gain any speed when performing blit
operations in planar, with bitplanes. In chunky you don't have
bitplanes so it makes no difference. It's even in fact slower to
handle interleaved output than to handle planar output.

So, after all this, you'll have to come up with a very good reason why
you need to be using interleaved chunky.

-- 
Paul.

