@NODE "Mail_307" "More OS friendly stuff"
From: Jake Frederick <gonzo@acadia.net>
Date: Mon, 26 Oct 1998 19:56:44 +0500
Subject: More OS friendly stuff

    Okay, I'm still trying to get the hang of this OS friendly programming
thing. I am quite comfortable with blitz mode but am having trouble converting
one of my games to Amiga mode. Here's a basic outline of my program, could
someone tell me how I should do it in an OS friendly manner?
  
    bitmap 0,640,170,8
    load bitmap 0,"blahblah",0 ;background pic
    copy bitmap 0,1
    bitmap 2,320,30,8
    load bitmap 0,"blablahhhh" ;score display

Now here's the part I'm really not sure of

    initcoplist 0,74,170,$13118,0,0,0
    initcoplist 1,44,30,$13108,0,256,0

Should I use two windows instead of coplists? Here's the rest in case there's
something else that could stand changing

    buffer 0,55000
    buffer 0,55000
    
    createdisplay 1,0
    displaypalette 0,0
    displaypalette 1,0
    
    ;Move shapes and stuff

    Vwait
    displaybitmap 0,akbit,x,y 
    akbit=1-akbit
    use bitmap akbit
    unbuffer akbit
    ;bblit shapes
    ;update score display in the same way

In case you couldn't figure it out, I'm just using a 320x200 display and
scrolling around on a 640x200 bitmap while blitting shapes and updating a
separate score display. Any tips would be appreciated. Thanks....
    

    
