@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_308" "Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 with ESMTP id <0F0Y0024KA0E9Z@hermes.ucd.ie> for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie;
 Sat, 17 Oct 1998 03:38:41 +0100 (BST)
Date: Fri, 16 Oct 1998 21:26:38 -0600 (CST)
From: Carlos Villarroel Cortes <carlosv@redes.unam.mx>
Subject: Most wanted Blitz Libs.
encoding: QUOTED-PRINTABLE

Please don't be afraid by the lenght of this mail, i'm gonna respond to
the last messages of both Paul's in this single mail.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------=
-

From=20the last -and lack of- mail responses i have realized
that some of you still are thinking some like the next:

I'm trying to revive the past...
Hardware bashing has gone...
Saying that Amiga hardware is special is a very visceral affirmation...

But actually, my point of view about the AMIGA hardware has some technical
background that most of you already know. I'll try to explain it with the
next facts:

* Always remember that ALL is relative.  The faster the CPU, the more
  stealed CPU cycles when accesing COMMON types of memory.
  So relatively more CPU time is wasted at memory access.

This have a pretty relevance in our Blitter discussion:  Think of a very
fast CPU, and a CPU routine that is going to write a bunch of words to the
relatively slow chip-ram.  The faster the CPU, the more CPU cycles wasted.
Even the standard 32 bit SIMM RAM are slow for the most recently CPU's out
there, so table access is also a pain for fast CPU's.

Unless you have a machine with UMA ( Unified Memory Architecture, only foun=
d
on very recent -and very expensive- SGI workstations, that's nothing more
than a virtually unlimited chip-mem connected to the CPU with a wide bus of
128 bit at very high clock speeds ) all the other architectures,-and all th=
e
amigas with graphics cards-, suffer of the same problem due the separation
between graphics mem and data mem.  Some of the most recent graphics cards
have 'solved' this problem doing some cache antics or using CPU
interruptions!

Considering those sort of things:

IT'S BETTER TO MINIMIZE THE ACCESS TO CHIP-RAM AND?! FAST-RAM! BY THE CPU.
So if we want to display a chunky buffer the best way to do it is: first
manage all the operations -with a register based scheme if possible- in the
buffer on fast-ram, and then, at the display stage, copy only the words
related to the buffer to be displayed...  and order the blitter to do the
rest...  ;).  (Using the properly queued list that are in the
VirtualBlitLibrary code:)

The same goes for the CPUBlit routines, they are going to waste a pretty
BIG CPU time when trying to write bobs to chip-ram. So, Why we must use a
VirtualBitmap Library? Simply because Amiga display hardware CAN do all the
map_display/bob_draw work. So this won't stealt a huge ammount of cycles
from the CPU, and if you still need mode BLIT power (really not needed if
we follow the method i have explained) you can use the CPU to move a big
bob -or a bunch of smaller bobs- on screen. This won't waste more CPU time
than a C2P routine. Of course if you want to do something really complex
with the image then you MUST use the Blitter assisted C2P routine.

* The next generation of Amigas will run actual programs mainly by
  emulation, so ALL the actual software/hardware bits MUST run without worr=
y.

Slightly slower naturally, unless the new hardware is going to be miles
ahead than AGA.

* Blitz Basic is very close to C, so a specially modified C compiler for
  the new CPU - a friendly thing with the basic Blitz libraries converted -
  could compile Blitz stuff.
  In the best case, the new hardware may be something downward compatible.
  In the worst case, the critical display libraries are the only thing to b=
e
  rewritten.

THIS IS WHERE WE NEED THE NEW THREE LIBRARIES THAT I'M PROPOSING.
They are the most efficient way to do blitter/display stuff, so they could
be the standards in AGA displays for screen/map/3d/chunky type games.  (All
currently known types).  And the whole conversion simply will need the
rewrite of these three libraries.  This will let us have NOW and in the
future the better and faster displays possible.
Again it's not a very hard work to do.

Do you remember the good old days when the computers where 8-bit wide?=20
Well, since then, the dream of all programmers on all platforms has been to
do a big and smooth screen scroll without worry about the technical part.
And without wasting all the machine resources, that is, without the need of
rewrite the entire screen every frame, That's what the VirtualBitmapLibrary
could do.  More over it virtually doesn't need any CPU cycles.  The blitter
can do the small work of writing a column, a row and some big main
characters every frame at 60 Hz while the CPU is doing some really useful
A.I.  stuff.  (And, with multitasking ON you can render a 3D anim in the=20
background or send/receive some data at the same time too).  So it worth at=
=20
least a fast look to the algorythm.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------=
-

>From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>

AT LAST!, Ladies and gentlemans, the one and only: Mr Paul Burkey at the
keyboard... answering one of my mails... WOW! :)

I was thinking that you have leaved the blitz-list to enter some C-list 8)

>Hi,
>
>>> not interested in these copper, blitter, or sprite screens. TBH I
>>> thought that this kind of hardware bashing went out with the A500.
>
