-------------------------------------------------------------------------=
=20

Date: 15 Oct 98 16:19:57 +0000
>From: Paul <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
>Subject: blitter c2p
>
>Carlos,
>
>I'm taking a look at the blitter-assisted c2p right now. I'm not
>looking at the `blitter screen' thing you posted, but at some c2p's
>which use the blitter for the final passes of a normally cpu-only
>chunky to planar conversion. From what I can tell, it uses
>graphics.library/qblit() and while it is performing the blits it
>allows you to call your cpu routines for processing the game or
>drawing bobs or whatever. So apparently time is gained in doing object
>processing in the time you'd normally be c2p'ing. However, the next
>c2p doesn't begin until the blitter conversion is finished.

Here helps the queue and the blitter finish interrupt bit, again in the
VBlit Lib.  code.  And you must use the VBlank interrupt to order this
every start of the current -and selected (some db here)- frame.  Maybe the
blitter-screen code can help much more as it does something like this.  But
anyway it's good a blitter assisted C2P to gain better resolutions.

>An
>alternative I think which could work is to have a doublebuffer so that
>you can begin the next c2p conversion as soon as you've set the
>blitter conversiong going, so that the two are working
>`asynchronously', although I think this will cause a lot of clashes in
>chipmem.

The trick relies in the classic db technique: blitter must finish his work
in the hidden frame before you show this and init the next conversion. So
you must use the CPU in paralell to fill the part that blitter can't reach
in the required frame rate.

>The other important thing I notice is that you cannot use the blitter
>to assist in conversion unless the chunky buffer is in CHIPRAM! This
>might be all very well for actual c2p display, but it is bad news for
>the actual rendering of pixels and such. So I really don't think
>there's going to be any gain had there.

True! you must do all of them before, in fast-ram.

>Yes, I believe it is true you
>can do faster c2p conversion using the blitter to help, BUT the price
>you pay for that is that all of your object rendering and so on is
>going to be to chipram so it really has little use on anything higher
>than low end 030's.

Again true!, this is why we must create a new routine that do all the
chunky stuff in fast and then only copy the buffer to chip -this MUST be
the only time that CPU will access Fast Ram-
With a blitter assisted routine you must the half CPU work in fast, and the
other half must be done by blitter. To gain some time, that is.=20
After all, the CPU's can be faster but the Video display is the same -and
blitter too-.  The most advanced consoles out there still don't handle a
better resolutions than 320x200 or 320x400(laced) with 256 colours.

>There are versions of the blitter-assisted c2p for
>030 optimisation and 040 optimisation, and it claims that both can
>perform a full conversion at `copyspeed', which I think translates as
>50-60fps. But the downside is that although the conversion to display
>is fast, the actual plotting of pixels and drawing of graphics is
>effeectively slowed down. So you lose any advantage you had a probably
>lose even more, which is why there isn't an 060 blitter-assisted
>routine.

With the method you are mentioning, yes, but remember, any CPU with any
C2P routine still need to do a copy from fast to chip of the converted
buffer. So if you transform/copy one half and only copy the other half.
Blitter can do the remainder half conversion.. (If you need really high
resolutions, that is)

>There is no way to make the blitter work in fastram and it is because
>of this that the blitter c2p is ineffective for 030/50 and upwards. It
>even states in the sourcecode that it is only really suitable for low
>end cpu's, which in my book means 020 and up to perhaps 030/33.
>Anything higher than that is going to lose efficiency due to the lag
>of writing pixels to chipram as well as attempting to convert chunky
>from and to chipram. It's bad enough converting TO chipram without
>having to read from it also, AND write to it for graphics work. I have
>looked quite hard at the code and I don't think it's intended that a
>fastram chunky buffer is used. A chunky buffer is reserved in chipram
>at the end of the program.

Again, we must complete a new routine to solve this problems.

>One suggestion might be to use a fastram
>chunky buffer, perform the first few passes of a conversion with full
>8-bitplane output to chunky, and then perform a further chipram
>conversion to complete the process using the blitter, but this means
>that surely the c2p would be half the speed so is not viable.

Ahh, moment! It's not viable if you aren't gonna to obtain an acceptable
frame-rate (30 FPS are very acceptable for now).  But blitter only can
manage 320x200 at 30 FPS, so if you want better resolutions/frame rate you
must remember the above comments: half CPU, half blitter.

>I don't
>think there is any two ways about it. If you want to use the blitter
>for a faster conversion you pay the price by having slower graphics
>rendering anyway and this is why it is probably reccommended to use
>normal cpu-only c2p's definately for 040 or higher, and probably for
>030/50 as well.
>
>So that's that idea pretty much out the window.

Surely these routine is bad, we must not be forced to have the chunky
buffer in chip-ram, this will slow down everything on faster CPU's.  The
new must be better, and at must try to find the better mem -accordly to the
CPU- to put it, or at least let the user to choose the destination of the
chunky buffer.

>However, one little brainwave I have had came when noticing that
>interlaced displays work faster than their non-interlaced equivelents.
>For example, a 640x512 PAL Hires Interlaced screen c2p's faster than
>the equivelent in DoublePal (DoublePal Hires Non-Laced). This is
>because there is effecively half as much data being displayed by the
>bitplane DMA, and as such this means there is more time to write to
>chipram with the c2p.

Surely!  Do you remember the 'trick with sprites that will let us have
better resolutions with a little flicker' i have mentioned, well it's
something like this but it's an odd 'vertical interlace' to double the
resolution at the same frame rate.  I'm no wrong, you can do this routine.

>Now, going on this basis, I have wondered what
>it would be like to have an interlaced c2p. This would especially
>apply to interlaced screens as, for example, only half of the display
>is ever visible in a single frame. So, if it were possible to do half
>the number of c2p lines in a single frame, and the other half in the
>next frame, there would be zero visual difference and yet double the
>throughput.

Yes, of course, we are now talking the same VIDEO amiga language :)
Still some can need a full 640x480 multiscan resolution, but again, if you
see the games in the most recent consoles, the high frame rate simply will
not let you count the lines, so no-one can note the difference between a
laced display and another that isn't.

>This would only work seamlessly in probably an interrupt
>driven c2p, however, and it'd have to be capable of converting half
>the display in a single frame (which isn't likely). So although this
>clarissa-style (SSA) trick isn't really viable but for perhaps 320x400
>interlaced on an 040/25 or higher, in which the c2p would run at about
>50fps and you'd think that it was doing full-screen update every
>frame,

Yea, the VBlank interrupt.

>it won't work so well in higher resolutions such as 640x512. I
>am not sure about 512x384 HighGFX though. But still, if you could do
>half a screen of interlaced per frame then you'd double your
>throughput.

True, a 640x200 (or 640x400 laces) 8-bit resolution aren't gonna work with
a 030/50.  But man, this is a very high resolution, you need only 320x200
(or 320x400 laced) to do a good game display.

>
>That aside, I am wondering if it would be a good idea to have an
>interlaced c2p which does `every other line' on an odd-line/even-line
>alternating basis per frame.=20

Of course this would be! The most amazing video effects are done in that
way, and they appears to be a full 640x400 resolution every 60th frame.
(or the PAL equivalent, although the flicker is less noticeable in NTSC)

>This way, for example, you could perform
>a c2p conversion of a 320x256 screen in about the amount of time it'd
>normally take to do just 320x128. The overall effect would be alike if
>there were a 320x256 interlaced screenmode, or iow the thickness of a
>rasterline would be 1 pixel instead of half a normal pixel. So the
>interlacing effect would be a bit more noticeable but would make for a
>much higher framerate, and given the framerate and the generally
>smooth movement of things on-screen it might prove to be viable. So
>I'm going to implement this in a minute to my most recent c2p, as it's
>a quite simply modification now that I have horizontal modulo support
>already. I'll let you know how I get on.

As always, we expect a good job from good guys.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------=
=20

