----
>Date: 15 Oct 98 19:36:58 +0000
>From: Paul <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
>Subject: interlaced c2p
>
>Carlos and co,
>
>I've done a test with interlaced c2p. Hmm. Well, as you might expect
>you get to double the number of objects you can do. Either that or you
>double your framerate. For example, 90 32x32 objects at 50fps,
>320x200 on an 040/25. However, it doesn't look too pretty.
>
>There is a strange artefact and I'm not sure I ever noticed it with
>interlaced screens, but if you move an object only 1 pixel in X and/or
>Y per frame, it gives the appearance of a doubling of the pixel size,
>because in the first frame you draw every even line of the object and
>then the next frame you do every odd line of the object, except that
>the object has moved one pixel so it's even again. It doesn't look too
>good. The artefact you get when moving horizontally is, as expected, a
>kind of `comb' at the edges, the width of which is the different in X
>positions from the previous frame and the current one.
>
>Further, when trying to do this in an actual interlaced screen, such
>as 320x400 PAL Lores laced, the effect is one of not being synched to
>the interlacing long/short frames, and gives the impression that the
>objects are moving at 16fps, but that they are moving two positions
>every frame. So that's isn't very appealing either. I was trying to
>think if there was another way to interlace the c2p operations,
>perhaps working in alternating verticle columns of 32 pixels. Like
>doing all of the first 32 pixels on all rows, missing the next 32,
>then doing the next 32 etc. So long as objects were to not cross the
>multiple of 32-pixel boundaries it would look okay, but where it
>crossed there'd be a horizontal effect. Although I think it would
>eliminate the verticle pixel-doubling thing. I am not sure if the
>pixel doubling occurs only for 1-pixel Y movement or just ODD numbered
>Y movements. I don't know if perhaps interlacing would help in hires
>and be less noticeable, I'll give that a try shortly.
>
>basically, whatever you can do at 25fps with full-screen c2p you can
>do at 50fps in interlaced or else double the number of objects. That's
>what it seems like anyway. It's just the appearance which is a bit
>undesirable.
>

Interlace is pretty tricky, if you aren't going to do it synced with the
VBlank interruption, i think you must at least do a VWAIT and next
instruction check the state of the Video Beam Position ($dff004) (with one
of the system functions or directly at hardware) before writting the next
frame. Anyway i think that without the IRQ, the routine isn't going to
work too smooth in severe multitasking. So first of all you must be sure
that you do all your operations in the correct frame (remember:  even,odd
video lines) and if possible turn multitasking off to do the tests without
worry about the correct video synchronization.

Please send a executable copy of your work to figure out more exactly the
problem, (a picture worth hundreds of words).

---------------------------------------------------------------------------=
--=20
>Date: 15 Oct 98 19:48:04 +0000
>From: Paul <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
>Subject: interlaced c2p
>
>Carlos and co,
>
>Just had another idea... the pixel-doubling effect that occurs
>vertically with an interlaced c2p, could be eliminated IF you coded
>your cpu-chunky-blit routines to render in interlaced also. This would
>additionally multiply the original number of bobs by 4!

That's true, a big 640x400 animation can be halfed if you select the
correct 640x200 frames. BUT.... You must be sure that your work are
going to work in a true stable and high frame rate (60 or 50 Hz).  So,
again, a VBlank IRQ is pretty recommended, or your display work can be
'desynchronizated' and this would lead to very bad results.

>IOW, you have
>to draw the bobs depending on the Y movement speed. If the speed is an
>odd number you start on the second line of the object. I think that's
>how it'd work. Just seems that if you're not displaying all lines then
>there's no reason to render all rows of all objects.

That's correct Paul!

>I think it'd be
>possible to therefore eliminate the verticle movement artefacts but
>you are still left with the horizontal comb effect.

We must see it in action...

Thanks for reading.

Carlos Villarroel
carlosv@cuk.redes.unam.mx


