@NODE "Mail_309" "Re: Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 19 Oct 1998 18:57:12 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 19 Oct 98 19:55:13 +0000
Subject: Re: Most wanted Blitz Libs.
Encoding: 7bit

Carlos,

I hope you enjoy this horrendously long message. ;-)

> * Always remember that ALL is relative.

Only relatively so.

> This have a pretty relevance in our Blitter discussion:  Think of a very
> fast CPU, and a CPU routine that is going to write a bunch of words to the
> relatively slow chip-ram.  The faster the CPU, the more CPU cycles wasted.
> Even the standard 32 bit SIMM RAM are slow for the most recently CPU's out
> there, so table access is also a pain for fast CPU's.

This is true but people are shifting to chunky cpu-work rather than
planar cpu-blits directly into chipram. It is true that chipram access
is relatively a lag on higher cpu's. But even so, another thing to
bear in mind is that if you are to use the blitter to do all your
objects it has to read from chipram as well as writing to it, and if
it is going to do masking it also has to read the existing destination
data. That's a lot of chipram access as opposed to using a cpu-blit
method possibly in combination with a fastram background store for
when doing masked blits. Also with the cpu background storage can
partly be performed at the same time as the part of a masked blit that
reads the existing data, possibly halving background storage time
(even if that's only about 1/6th of the overall BBlit time).
 
> IT'S BETTER TO MINIMIZE THE ACCESS TO CHIP-RAM AND?! FAST-RAM! BY THE CPU.

It is in ALL respects best to minimise chipram access at all costs.
However, this also includes using a blitter which works exclusively in
chipram for blitting, for background store, for background restore,
for masking and anything else.

In the first version of the beginnings of my tanks game I had a planar
method of doing things. This was before I got into chunky and c2p. I
had a planar superbitmap in fastram and I copied from it straight into
chipram, 320x210. It ran a little over 50fps. When I converted it to
chunky and chunky to planar it still ran at the same framerate, except
that now all blits and objects are done in chunky which is more
efficient for blitting.

> So if we want to display a chunky buffer the best way to do it is: first
> manage all the operations -with a register based scheme if possible- in the
> buffer on fast-ram,

I agree so far,

> and then, at the display stage, copy only the words
> related to the buffer to be displayed...

The longwords you mean, we don't work in words when it comes to
chipram. The suggestion of working in words is from the OCS/ECS and
blitter days where everything was handled in multiples of words.

> and order the blitter to do the
> rest...  ;).  (Using the properly queued list that are in the
> VirtualBlitLibrary code:)

This is all very well but you still can only do so many blits with the
blitter even in the most highly optimised queue based on a blitter
interrupt in optimised assembler, because it's still working in
chipram and chipram is slower than fastram.

> The same goes for the CPUBlit routines, they are going to waste a pretty
> BIG CPU time when trying to write bobs to chip-ram.

Relatively speaking yes there is a usage of cpu time in order to
handle blits. But you may also find that the main reason people use
the cpu in the first place is in order to blit more objects at the
same framerate as was possible with the blitter, so you are gaining.
It might be true that amount of objects gained with the cpu balances
out against having to use the cpu at all, but when what people want to
see is more objects than the blitter can provide what else are they
going to do but alter their priorities?

> So, Why we must use a
> VirtualBitmap Library? Simply because Amiga display hardware CAN do all the
> map_display/bob_draw work.

But it can't that's the problem. Even if you had properly queued
blits, the total maximum blitter capability is less than is possible
with the cpu. When I was writing my fruit machine I did tests to what
maximum size reels I could have in 32 colours while maintaining 25fps.
I think I managed to work out that it could do about 3 reels at
something like 48x150. That was doing a simple _unmasked_ copy from
one place to another, like an unmasked blit. That was the total
maximum it could do. On an 040/25 you can do probably 3-4 times the
amount.

However, admittedly at that stage you will have used up all your cpu
time, whereas with the blitter routine you will not have used much at
all. I think that's what you're trying to say isn't it?

The big question is, is a combination of blitter and cpu able to
outperform the cpu on its own.

It's a complicated question, much to consider. For a start there's the
problem that anything the blitter handles must be in chipram, and the
fact that anything the cpu handles must generally be in fastram. If
you coul blit, say, 10 32x32 objects without having used much cpu time
at all, you're going to have more cpu-time spare than if you blitted
those 10 objects /using/ the cpu. However, it may be possible in fact
that the person's game doesn't /need/ that much cpu-time. naturally,
if a game can run a whole loop with /time to spare/ then all this
worry about methods is unimportant. Not to say they couldn't therefore
enhance their performance by adding to what the game does. So the
question then is can more additional work be done in combination with
the blitter than without it.

But further than that, you have to ask if it's possible to use the cpu to do
effective blitting work of any kind if you are not going to be using chunky to
planar, AND also wether the chipram access that the blitter performs will hinder
the capability of doing any additional graphics work with the cpu. It is for
certain that for most modern games the blitter is too slow, so it more than
likely looks like we'll have to look to the cpu for some help. You say that the
blitter can be set up to handle full tile-scrolling and object blitting. This
might well be true for the scrolling and a few objects. But then what? What
hapens when you want to add another 20 objects and the blitter is already maxxed
out? If you were to then attempt to use a planar cpu-blit you would be trying to
access chipram that is already exhausted its access so the game is going to slow
down. So you then ask if that slowdown could be avoided by using the cpu-only, ie
perhaps the cpu could blit more objects to chipram than the blitter can in the
same space of time. Certainly this would mean that the cpu uses up some of its
processing time that you might think was better spent being free, but what the
hell are you going to use a spare 68040/25Mhz cpu for if you aren't going to do
any graphics work with it? Surely no game is likely to require so much processing
that you need an 040 just to handle the player movement and stuff. Games were
written perfectly adequately on a 68000 or 68020.

Once you've used the blitter to handle the scrolling and objects, if you have a
kind of game that can use tile scrolling that is, then what method are you going
to do to have optimum cpu-blitting in addition? If you are, as you admit
yourself, to use planar cpu-blits then you will hinder the cpu due to chipram
access speed (which would at that point be minimal). Using the blitter is like
saying that it's a clever little chap that you'd like to do some of the work but
the thing is that it gets under your feet also. To do effective graphics work
with the cpu you have to work in chunky because the chipram limits are too great
- decreased further if the blitter is doing stuff, and that is when it becomes
necessary to use chunky to planar.

You try and do 100 32x32 objects using planar cpu-blit and compare it to using a
chunky to planar routine that refreshes the entire screen in additional to doing
that many objects. For a start, all the chipram access required to blit the
planar objects directly into chipram will radically lower the framerate. When I
was doing tests on my planar tanks game I found that about a 320x400 area could
be copied to chipram _in one go_ at 25 frames a second. And yet, the fact is that
using chunky with a chunky to planar routine you can do more like 320x600 worth
of graphics work at 25fps including c2p time (040/25Mhz). The result for an 060
cpu or even an 040/40 is going to be even higher, a speed which chipram access
simply cannot match.

So, inevitably, if you are going to use the cpu alongside the blitter the blitter
WILL hinder the cpu. But, the blitter in some respect pays for this hinderence by
doing some of your graphics work. The question is wether the sum total of the
blitters work, minus the blitter's hinderence on the cpu, plus cpu blitting done
in the remaining time, is greater than blitting performed with the cpu only. What
do you think the answer is? Can blitter+cpu do more work than cpu alone, given
that using the blitter at all restrains the amount of available chipram time
available to the cpu.?

> So this won't stealt a huge ammount of cycles
> from the CPU,

Yes it will.

Okay so the set up of the blitter releases the cpu very much earlier than without
a properly queud blitter. However, stop to think of the effect that using the
blitter has on the cpu. How are you going to get any graphics work done with the
cpu into chipram, especially when it's being hogged by the blitter? Is the amount
of restrained cpu work plus the amount of blitter work greater than what the cpu
could do on its own using chunky to planar?

> and if you still need more BLIT power (really not needed if
> we follow the method i have explained)

What do you mean not needed? Many games nowadays are having more and more
animation, more and more things moving around, and in more colours. And what with
support for graphics cards which comes usually with hires modes, requiring
considerable amounts of graphics to be handled in fastram, do you reckon you're
going to make any impact on that using the blitter? Nope, graphics card output is
not in chipram. And do you think that someone is going to want to write two
versions of their code?

> you can use the CPU to move a big
> bob -or a bunch of smaller bobs- on screen.

Can you? Once the blitter is going full-pelt handling the scrolling and the
limited number of objects it can do, you think there is going to be much
possibility of blitting /anything/ to chipram with any great speed?

> This won't waste more CPU time
> than a C2P routine.

No but it wastes more cpu time simple because anything you want to do in addition
to the blitter is hindered by the fact that the blitter is working in chipram.

> Of course if you want to do something really complex
> with the image then you MUST use the Blitter assisted C2P routine.

It doesn't work like that. The blitter assisted c2p works in chipram. The entire
chunky buffer has to be in chipram. Either you have to copy it there every frame,
which on higher processors would take the same amount of time as a full 1x1
chunky to planar conversion of the entire data anyway, or you'd c2p half of it as
you say and then blit the other half which /still/ requires copying a full screen
to chipram. Do you realise it takes precicely the same amount of time to do that
copy as to do a full c2p operation? THEN you'd have to do further blitter
conversion time on top. There's no point. And nobody in their right mind wants to
do graphics work using the cpu in chipram.
 
> * The next generation of Amigas will run actual programs mainly by
>   emulation, so ALL the actual software/hardware bits MUST run without worry.

And? They will.
 
> Slightly slower naturally, unless the new hardware is going to be miles
> ahead than AGA.

Well if you're saying that future amigas will still have the qblit function and
use a much faster blitter in a much faster display then yes you are right that it
will be considerably faster, but then anything else including cpu-blitting will
also likely be faster as well.
 
> * Blitz Basic is very close to C, so a specially modified C compiler for
>   the new CPU - a friendly thing with the basic Blitz libraries converted -
>   could compile Blitz stuff.
>   In the best case, the new hardware may be something downward compatible.
>   In the worst case, the critical display libraries are the only thing to be
>   rewritten.

You'd have to be rethinking the ENTIRE game engine if you were writing for one of
those super amigas.
 
> They are the most efficient way to do blitter/display stuff, so they could
> be the standards in AGA displays for screen/map/3d/chunky type games.  (All
> currently known types).  And the whole conversion simply will need the
> rewrite of these three libraries.  This will let us have NOW and in the
> future the better and faster displays possible.
> Again it's not a very hard work to do.

And it's practically no effort to work in chunky already with graphics card
support, as the graphis card output will simply go to the new gfx card output in
a new Amiga.
 
> Do you remember the good old days when the computers where 8-bit wide? 
> Well, since then, the dream of all programmers on all platforms has been to
> do a big and smooth screen scroll without worry about the technical part.

You're suggesting this is for free. It's not. If you use the blitter to handle
your scroll you make it very difficult to use the cpu for any additional graphics
work, and as I say, it is very likely that a person WILL want more graphics. They
aren't just going to use the cpu for purely non-graphical processing.

> And without wasting all the machine resources, that is, without the need of
> rewrite the entire screen every frame,

Okay so a tile-based scroll method in chipram is much more efficient than a
cpu-based full-screen update, but then you are also stuck with the fact that your
game is running in a chipram screen, and any graphics work you want to do on it
has to write seprate operations to chipram. Beyond a certain point it is more
efficient to do a full screen update. Admittedly c2p is an overhead and you could
double your graphics throughput if the amiga had a native chunky display, but the
amount of work you can do with the blitter does have limits and using it _at all_
further places limits on what the cpu can do.

> That's what the VirtualBitmapLibrary
> could do.  More over it virtually doesn't need any CPU cycles.  The blitter
> can do the small work of writing a column, a row and some big main
> characters every frame at 60 Hz while the CPU is doing some really useful
> A.I.  stuff.

Yea, must be dam really useful if it's going to take up all the time that a 68040
or 68060 has.

> (And, with multitasking ON you can render a 3D anim in the 
> background or send/receive some data at the same time too).

Who in their right mind wants to render a 3d anim at the same time? If they've
got a powerful processor under the hood they want to see a game that uses it. Who
wants to play a game really that doesn't make any use of their system?

> So it worth at 
> least a fast look to the algorythm.

And I've looked at it and I believe it only applies on very low end machine and
in very narrow circumstances where you are needing a tile-based scroll like a
platform game or such. But only in one playfield, you can't do any clever
background animations or anything like that, you have a limit on the amount of
objects you can do and trying to do additional work with the cpu is going to
lower the framerate..

These days the main part of a modern game's processing is going to be the
graphics. There isn't enough game processing required that'd use the entirity of
a higher-end processor's time, and the new types of game engine coming out such
as 3d and stuff is totally unfeasible with normal chipram methods. If you want a
single playfield platform game or something then go ahead with the library but
otherwise it is firmly established that the features of AGA simply restrain
creativity and design possibilities that are possible when working solely with
the cpu for graphics work.

Also if you have read anywhere about future compatibility you might know that it
is suggested you do NOT use hardware sprites and that you do NOT use custom
copperlists and that you do NOT use the blitter. This is one major reason why
people are starting to treat AGA as just a display device. That's all I treat it
as now in my projects. It is simply a thing to view a 256-colour or ham8 graphic,
and even less of the ham8 too. This way you also are supporting the essence of
every graphis card with simple 256-colour display, no frills of hardware sprites
and such, and until there is reliable library support for the special features of
graphics cards that's the way it'll stay.
 
> >This kind of hardware bashing just isn't viable if you're thinking of writing
> >a game that will be accepted by the majoraty of users.
 
> It's not so bashing ;)

I think what Paul Burkey means is that it is using hardware features that are not
supported by all display devices. Yes you can do sprites and blitter and
copperlist with the o/s but you can't get those things to easily work on a
graphics card, and some may not even have those features at all. The interest is
in portability and future proofing, and that means you don't rely on things which
are not a consistent feature.

> well, in fact the copper is used for ONE LINE of
> work in the VirtualBitmapLib.

Do you mean it has to work in blitz mode?

> and the sprites don't ever need to be used!
> So i'm only using the blitter and in a very system friendly way.

Okay but then how are you going to make this blitter-based game have graphics
card support? Write chunky graphics routines of course. So if you are going to do
that it means that you might as well not bother messing about with two methods of
doing the graphics and just stick with one. It makes it much easier. For example,
I don't have a graphics card but because I am only using AGA as a display device
with no frills, and am working in chunky, I add graphics card support with a
single line of code, which is a lot less than all the extra routines necessary to
handle the possibility of using the blitter system.

> (Remember:  system friendy = multitasking)

Just because it multitasks doesn't necessarily mean it's friendly ;-)

> And the majority of the Amiga users do not have a 4000 with graphics card!
> And sure that it will be accepted if it's good and let multitasking on!

Some of what you say is valid if you are not targetting graphics cards but many
games publishers these days particularly look for gfx card support in order to
appeal to the largest audience possible.
 
> Still i know a huge ammount of people that does 3Danim/image
> processing/internet works in one accelerated A1200.

What has this to do with games tho?

> But you are true, they're the ones with the money, and we must support
> them. Anyway, they have AGA also :) so if a game runs better in AGA mode,
> they CAN use the AGA mode.

Yea but some people cannot run AGA at the same time as a graphics card, Paul
Burkey being an example of that. And once people have a graphics card they
probably don't want to have wind of AGA ever again. The shift is now towards a
graphics card as the primary display device with backgwards compatibility for
AGA. You aren't going to see many more AGA-only games on the market.

And although I dislike it when people just try to throw in as much technical
features as possible thinking it makes the game good, it has to still be said
that it appeals.
 
> >You understand that the
> >Amigas custom hardware is very special, so you will realise that gfx-cards
> >can't do most of the things that AGA can.
> 
> That's the point man, that's the point.

But you're saying it as though this is the good fact about AGA. But I'm afraid
that for the majority of things it isn't. If you want to make a simple little PD
game then AGA is fine. But if you have any ambitions or looking for it to be a
larger project you are going to be thinking of seriously questioning the AGA
features.

Even with AGA the hardware sprites have started to be phased out, in that some
monitor drivers place limits on the number of sprites that are free for use. The
system wants a sprite for the mousepointer and uses others for scrolling. So you
can't rely on that. The copper lets you have pretty rainbows and perhaps easier
access to multiple screens/resolutions on the same display, but those kind of
features are losing appeal also.
 
> First, if the game is going to be of chunky type; the blitter C2P library
> will do all the work for the AGA ones.

But it won't. It has drawbacks and unnecessary ramifications. Think for a minute.

You want to do a blitter-assisted c2p operation. You want all your graphics to be
handled in fastram. Chipram is out of the question for that.

So what do you do? You've got a whole 320x200 screen in fastram and you want to
get it into chipram.

Options are:

a) Chunky to planar the entire 320x200 area to chipram using the cpu.

b) Chunky to planar part of the 320x200 area to chipram, and copy the rest of the
area to chipram ready for the blitter.

You are suggesting that option B is better. It's not. Look at the chipram access.
Are you familiar with the term "copy speed"? It is the speed at which data can be
copied from one place to another without any processing of the data. Modern 1x1
chunky to planar routines work at the same speed as a straight copy on anything
from an 040/40 upwards, and an 040/25 is pretty dam fast also.

So what is making you say that it will be faster to c2p only part of the screen
from fastram, and to copy the rest? The copying of the rest takes the same amount
of time as it would take to do the conversion to planar in the first place! Any
time you then waste using the blitter is totally a loss.

The other option is to have the buffer in chipram already. This means reads from
chipram as well as writes and that's not pretty, especially that all graphics
have to be rendered to chipram. You cannot do it all in fastram and then simply
copy it to chipram because you could do a c2p in precicely the same amount of
time, there's no point.

Basically, if you want to work in chunky you use fastram for everything and a
chunky to planar routine to convert the whole display to chipram.

If you're going to do this what are you going to use the blitter for? If you're
gunna have it working chipram it slows down the chunky to planar conversion.

The blitter simply isn't necessary and has no purpose for chunky work.

The only thing I can think of is that the time inbetween the c2p being finished
and the loop doing its processing ready for the next c2p to start, could be a
time in which the blitter could write some objects to chipram, as there is no
chipram access during that period. That actually sounds like a good idea. The
only problem is that you cannot reproduce this for graphics card support without
having to use a lot more cpu time and so the graphics card version will run
slower than AGA or else not have those AGA features. This still doesn't mean I
favour using the blitter, however, as it is still not futureproof. The only thing
I can rely on is working in 256-colour chunky.

However, as it is often a nice thing when a game has special features for when
you've got graphics card or higher cpu's, maybe it'd be an idea to have extra
features for when you've got AGA. But you've still got to do additional coding to
make this possible.

> So you don't have to worry about
> programming the blitter and these sort of stuff.

_Somebody_ has got to worry about programming this library at some point.

> You only need to program
> the graphics card antics. In fact, any type of game can be programmed this
> way.

And if you are going to program the graphics card antics you HAVE to work in
chunky, and generally you copy the chunky buffer in its entirity to the graphics
card. So why not use the same blit routines and simply replace the WPA8() with
C2P() for AGA?

> Second, if the game is going to be a platform; the VirtualBitmap and the
> VirtualBlit libraries are going to do all the hard work.

Only in the old-style platform games. Modern platform games have multiple layers
of parallax, and not in any low number of colours either. Such things require
chunky and full-screen updates, unless you are just going to regurgitate the same
old engine. Okay so higher resolutions are more possible with a chipram tile
method, but ONLY so far as the scrolling is concerned. Again, it might make it
faster to work with this in chipram as for the blitter-c2p but the side-effect is
that the cpu is hindered. ANYTHING you do in chipram hinders the cpu, regardless.
That is, if you want to have any decent amount of things happening graphics-wise,
and as Paul Burkey rightly said there are far more pixel-specific effects you can
do in chunky more efficiently than in planar.

People don't just want flat 2d graphics any more. 2 dimensional games these days
need to have a more three dimensional feel, and you can't do that simply with
just ordinary bobs.

> So you will only
> need to setup your map in fast-ram, copy the graphics to chip-ram and
> specify the main bob's and the virtual screen positions like if you where
> working with a inmense hardware bitmap.

Okay, that's simple enough and will work. But what then, what about all the other
bobs? What about any parallax you want? If you think you're going to use the cpu
for that how is the cpu going to work? A normal planar cpu-blit from fastram
direct to chipram? You won't get much done that way in any space of time! You
can't work in chunky when you're using the blitter for planar because c2p becomes
out of the question. Even if you were using the blitter only and running at
25fps, any additional cpu work would lower the framerate. It's better to stop the
cpu at least at half its capability and throw the cpu in, or even better get rid
of the blitter altogether and just use the cpu.

> It's all but huge work. And this
> will work better and faster than any graphics card, that's for sure ;)

And what about the graphics card code? A complete rewrite of your graphics code
just to allow graphics card support? Everything you add in planar has to be added
in chunky.

> Why?  because they don't need virtually any CPU time to be wasted and
> don't overload the Chip Ram bus.

And you think the blitter doesn't hog the chipram bus? You cannot feasibly mix
bliter and cpu graphics. Blitter and cpu-nongraphics perhaps, but for that you
don't really need much cpu power and so higher cpu's are wasted.

> Commercially i haven't seen any like this
> before, but you can be sure that this will be faster than any other.

What do you mean? It's been done before, doen to the death. Do you think nobody's
done proper queued blits before, nobody done super-optimised assembler
tile-scrollers? Superfrog springs to mind, as does Zool. And how many bobs were
moving around? Hardly any, and they were at 25fps if you were lucky. Gone are the
days of moving a sprite around on top of a pretty background picture. That isn't
enough interaction.

> So, these libraries are going to do the hard AGA work for us.

And who is going to do the hard AGA work to make these libraries?

> And talented
> programmers like you can concentrate in doing a better and faster game
> engine -or including support for one or two (or three or...) graphics card-
> rather than going into these AGA technical stuff.

You don't need to do it like that. If you have graphics card support via WPA8()
it should support all cards, via cybergraphics or picasso or whatever.
 
> >The Amigas hardware display has been dropped by all major game
> >developers. 
> 
> That's true, before us, some programmers where saying that amiga hardware
> display is slow, that can't do any fast c2p conversion, that blitter is
> crap, etc.

Maybe because after a point this is true. Okay so if you have only got an 020
then using the blitter is essential, but how many have only got 020 and for how
long and what kind of future has a product got if targetted at such a
specificaton? Like you said it's about relativity and it's unfortunately a fact
that all other platforms are bounding on ahead in their technical specs which
makes the kind of games you might like for nostalgia reasons on the amiga start
to look a bit lacking. You comment about the amiga not getting the respect it
deserves, and are interested in pushing it to its limits, but don't want to
aknowledge that the harware features have had it.

> But these people are trying to do a smooth scroll filling two
> complete screens (for db, that is)

You don't need to do any double buffering when you use chunky. The only think
double buffered is the /viewable/ memory, which means chipram, so you perhaps
have a double buffer for the output from the c2p. That has absolutely no effect
on processing time.

> every frame using only the blitter, in
> synchronous mode with the CPU,

Yes but think about this almighty `free time' synchronous mode. It isn't really
so free after all. You ARE likely going to want more graphics than the blitter
alone can provide and trying to mix the cpu with _planar_ graphics to chipram is
going to be very inefficient use of the cpu power, whereas using the cpu on its
own could well achive much greater results. Okay so c2p is not feasible for 50fps
but 25fps is pretty good, or 30 or whatever.

> and then, they intend to draw big main bobs
> on the same screen with CPUBlit commands. More over, they want all this in
> 8 bitplanes.  That's for sure that this will slowdown everything. 90% of
> the games aren't programmed in the most optimal way.

If you did most of the main graphics work with the blitter, how are you going to
finish off the graphics work? Using the cpu - accessing a chipram that is already
slow but now hogged by the blitter. The high end processors are going to be
sitting idle most of the time. It's all very well giving all this graphics work
to the blitter but what are you going to use the cpu for when it's free? You
already have to use it for processing the game, so what else are you going to do,
because sure as hell your game isn't going to be so sophisticated that it needs
an 040 just to handle the movement of objects, AI and so on. When people get
higher cpu's, ie 040's and 060's they want to see things happening faster, and
you see only the graphics, not the stuff under the hood.
 
> >Name one Amiga game that has been released in the last
> >two years (Since Worms) that actually *uses* the Amigas hardware
> >and does it in a way that makes gfx-cards look unnecessary. 

An example in point, worms did look quite nice, lots of parallax and so on. But
the price of this was that the main graphic was only 16 colours dithered, and the
worms were tiny little runts, and there wasn't really much else animating other
than little bullets and shells and stuff like that. Maybe yes it ran on lower end
machines but then of course it's not using the processor and it certainly didn't
multitask.
 
> none until now, wait a moment... i have heard of a FlashBack clone...

Have you see the cangy (sp) game demo, a cd-rom platformer? It uses tonnes of
hardware sprites. But it looks crap.

> but anyway it doesn't have smooth scroll, the screens are statics.
> But we can change it :)
> Also, some graphics card are impressive but they are most intended to do
> serious stuff.

There are also fundamentally an output device just like AGA is, and its on those
grounds that the game code connects and allows seamless aga and gfx-card support
via chunky.

> In the games department, even some 32 bit consoles 
> (in no way miles ahead of an AGA display) can do it equal or better. 

Oh? Consider for example the Sega Megadrive. It might be a bit old but you sure
as hell won't see sonic the hedgehog running on an amiga in the same amount of
colours at with the same smoothness. It ran at a solid 50Hz permanently with
tonnes of layers of parallax and multiple playfields at tremendously high speeds
you'd be hard pushed to do with a tile-based system. Some people had a go at
doing something similar with that `kid chaos' thing which was meant to be pushing
the machines hardware to its limits, but what was the end result? Not exactly
stunning was it. And gosh I shudden to think of `quick the thunder rabbit' with
its glorious 3-colour main character. And Mr Nutts wasn't much good either.

They are all hardware-using games using sprites and blitter and such and they
really weren't very good. They're very old-hat. The technical spec just hinders
your creativity. You don't want to have to think about how many objects you can
do or what you're limited to, letting the hardwre define what is possible. People
like to liberate their wishes and unleash their desires in a 68040 free-for-all.
 
> Your game must be pretty complex.  Anyway the sort of programming you
> are doing for this can be speed up with a blitter c2p library (at least for
> a 320x200 screen).  (I think the old settlers is a pretty fine engine
> implemented in a block style map.  There is no other way to do it in 512K
> of chip-ram.)

Yes, I do agree that the chipram scroll method is very fast as it is very close
to the native data format, ie planar, working directly on the data that you view.
But although it was the best way at the time it just isn't effective anymore.
 
> That is true, as you have used a chunky buffer, but the C2P conversion
> MUST be done by blitter since your game need all the CPU it can get.

If he uses the blitter for part of the c2p he will not see any speed increases,
only speed losses.

Blitter-assisted c2p's are only designed for low end cpu's.
 
> A little not-so-hard work for a while can let us make the most optimal
> games ever done in any amiga language.

So do it then! :-)
 
> >I'm a great fan
> >of he Amigas 'demo scene' and I'm always impressed by the effects
> >that can be achieved... However, almost all of todays 'AGA Demo's'
> >are based around chunky buffer rendering and optimized c2p so
> >even thats a bad example of AGA at it's best. 
> 
> It's only a small part of what AGA can do :)

Sure, but that doesn't mean that using the other things that AGA can do is going
to prove a better option. I remember the days of non-chunky demos well and all
the effects were done in planar. It is simply that after a certain point new
effects were not possible in planar as the chipram was too limiting. It is the
same with games. Yes it might be possible to do a fairly decent thing with the
AGA features but it won't be as good as cpu-based systems.
 
> Thats true, AGA is a display device.  But it was intended to do VIDEO
> display (remember, Jay Miner have designed this with Video Games in mind).

Regardless of what it was intended to do, the fact is that in this day and age
its primary use is as a display device. Amiga nostalgia is all very well and
patriotic but "it doesn't pay the bills" so to speak. By that I don't mean defect
to the PC, as the AGA chipset isn't the entirity of what makes an Amiga.

> At this department, the Amiga's hardware is perfectly capable of display a
> 640x200 or 640x400-interlaced 8 BitPlane

Not many people want to play an interlaced game, it is not good on the eyes
without upping the Hz and that means slowing down the chipram access further.

> -also HAM8, another pretty 
> bright idea since it can compress by default from 24 to 8 bits-
> complex animations in full screen at 60 HZ. Only try ANIM 32 from Scala to
> mention something.

Okay Ham8 is a good idea, it's hardware, but again you don't get nothing for
nothing. You lose colour accuracy, you lose flexibility of pixel-specific colour
choice, and rendering is made much more complicated. It may be okay for title
screens and stuff but 256 colours is also adequate if done well.
 
> And yes, the amiga hardware display have it's limits when you intended to
> access all of them from the CPU (due the reasons exposed before). So it's
> what WE NEED THE LIBRARIES I'M ALREADY PROPOSED!, we must minimize the
> AGA graphics access from the CPU!

Not only from the cpu. We must minimise chipram access FULL STOP.

Just because you're working with the blitter doesn't mean you're gaining time. It
DOES have an effect on the cpu because the cpu cannot efficiently do any planar
graphics work while supporting the blitter and the size of people's graphics
these days they don't want them kept in chipram. One of the main reasons I moved
to fastram is because there isn't enough chipram to hold the size screens I want
and the number of sound samples I want.

> But we have two copprocesors and a pretty
> fine hardware display that can do it virtually by themselves!

Yes, they can, as you keep stating. BUT, as *I* keep stating, that doesn't mean
that doing so is the most effective or efficient method!

Just because it might be easier to do something one way doesn't mean its the best
way.

> That's true, you must use a C2P routine. (Blitter C2P if possible :)

I am using c2p. But there is no feasible need for a blitter-assisted c2p. None at
all. The time taken to copy the data to chipram is EQUAL to the time it'd take to
convert it to planer with the CPU. Precicely the same cpu-time needed for both,
and I sure as hell am not working with a chipram chunky buffer.
   
> A fast look to the VirtualBlit Lib. code can give you some ideas. the queue
> is here, waiting for C2P blitter instructions.

Forget it, it's a naff idea. Sorry, but that's the fact. It sounds good in theory
but it will not be effective in practice.
 
> >Well for one thing working in Amiga mode, which is my choice, doesn't
> >very easily allow you to do copperlists or hardware sprites. Yes it's
> >possible and I've done it before but it isn't exactly simple and who
> >is going to write a game that relies on hardware sprites when they
> >wont work on graphics cards. It means more code.
 
> Again this is the very reason of why we need a standard library that can do
> the AGA work for us.

Who cares where the work comes from? Wether it's from my own program or some
shared library the fact remains more work is needed.

> That's ok, but if you are going to do this pretty complex stuff, it's
> better to use a Blitter C2P routine only.

Huh? Why? Why on earth? There is no reason to. It is NOT better.

> I'm already have explained the
> sort of games that can take advantage of the first two library prospects:
> isometric and platforms.

I think you're living in the past to be honest. You're thinking of games that
have come and gone already. Those kind of platformers with one playfield and
limited colours and limited animation is just no good anymore. It's done to the
death. I don't know why you think you're doing something new, it's not new at
all.

> Amiga harware is pretty capable of do these with
> ease and freeing virtually all the CPU.

Freeing it to do what? Sit on its arse? Roll up roll up, anyone want a 68060/50
cpu spare not allowed to do any graphics processing? What can we use it for?
 
> Something like Worms but in a bigger scale, that's true, you really need a
> big chunky buffer. These days we can afford the price of memory so it's
> viable indeed.  Anyway, the old Settlers scenery/animation is also pretty
> complex and it can be done with 512K of chipram. So certainly it doesn't
> use a chunky buffer. We must take a look at these code some day.

All this "we" you keep coming out with. This is YOUR project. You are the only
person that seems to be truly interested in these methods. They're old-hat. Move
on. It's all outdated this stuff you're suggesting. A lot of work for little or
no gain. Software design is moving in a different direction to simply how
efficiently the system is using its capabilities or wether all the little
hardware extras are being used to the full.
 
> >I may look into the blitter assisted c2p's this afternoon. Maybe I can
> >figure it out now that I am much more familiar with the structure of
> >the routines.
> 
> I'm sure again :)

Well no. I looked. I understand how it works. But I am not going to convert it to
blitz. There is no point. Nobody who wants to work in chunky will want to work in
chipram chunky buffers. The aim is to SPEED UP graphics work not slow it down.

> Here helps the queue and the blitter finish interrupt bit, again in the
> VBlit Lib.  code.  And you must use the VBlank interrupt to order this
> every start of the current -and selected (some db here)- frame.

Yea I know how to do it. It's just not worth it.

> Maybe the
> blitter-screen code can help much more as it does something like this.  But
> anyway it's good a blitter assisted C2P to gain better resolutions.

The blitter screen code is for a 2x2 system only.

Blitter assisted c2p requires the buffer in chipram. That's no good. Death to it!
Burn it! Down with it! Let go of the past man, I mean, the blitter is basically
a limitation on imagination, design, possibility and creativity. Everyone knows
it. Nobody likes it, everyone is moving away from it or has already done so.
They're not missing anything, they haven't neglected to think of how to use the
system more effevtively. Fact is the blitter and such is outdated and ineffective
for the things that people want to do.

> The trick relies in the classic db technique: blitter must finish his work
> in the hidden frame before you show this and init the next conversion.

What do you mean `init the next conversion'? Copy the buffer to chipram? Where do
you think you'll get the time to do this?

If your buffer is in fastram it will be at a LOSS to c2p part of it and copy the
other part for blitter use.

> So
> you must use the CPU in paralell to fill the part that blitter can't reach
> in the required frame rate.

Huh? I don't think you understand what the blitter-assistance does. It is not
possible to do a c2p /solely/ with the blitter AFAIK, which is why it is only
/assistance/. It does some parts that are possible to do in the blitter. That's
all. And the only benefit of doing it is if you hvae a low end 030 cpu and aren't
therefore doing very much graphics work.
 
> >The other important thing I notice is that you cannot use the blitter
> >to assist in conversion unless the chunky buffer is in CHIPRAM! This
> >might be all very well for actual c2p display, but it is bad news for
> >the actual rendering of pixels and such. So I really don't think
> >there's going to be any gain had there.
> 
> True! you must do all of them before, in fast-ram.

Then what? Copy it to chipram? The copy to chip ram takes precicely the same
amount of time as a complete c2p conversion on anythng from an 040/40 upwards and
almost so on an 040/25. Gotta think to the future. People aren't writing games
for 68020, it's too limiting to the possibilities you want to manifest.

> Again true!, this is why we must create a new routine that do all the
> chunky stuff in fast and then only copy the buffer to chip -this MUST be
> the only time that CPU will access Fast Ram-

That's rubbish though, sorry. You're completely misled on this. For a start,
doing a chunky to planar conversion in FASTRAM only (with fastram output) only
works about 20% faster than with chipram output! This is because a c2p routine is
design by `those who know how', very skilled binary-sculpters who know every
trick there is to know to ooze efficiency from their code. And they have designed
the c2p so that it is converting the data while copying to chipram. It is because
chipram is slower than the cpu that the routine is able to do processing
inbetween each longword write, and as such on higher processors the conversion is
almost transparent as far as the end result and speed are concerned. There is no
point thinking that just copying the data from fastram to chipram is going to
allow you to gain time because in the time it takes to do a straight copy you can
do a c2p conversion. There's no point copying the data and letting the blitter
finish it off. No point at all. And as I said, nobody wants a chipram chunky
buffer.

> With a blitter assisted routine you must the half CPU work in fast, and the
> other half must be done by blitter.

And how does the blitter get its data? It either has to be copied from fastram or
live in chipram. Neither has any benefit at all.

> To gain some time, that is. 

No, to only lose time.

> After all, the CPU's can be faster but the Video display is the same -and
> blitter too-.

True but it is only /memory access/ that is a hinderence to the cpu. The cpu does
not wait for a write to chipram to be finished before it presses on with further
register-based calculations (ie the c2p conversion), so in the same amount of
time it takes to do all the reading and writing from memory, the cpu is working
very hard and efficiently at converting the data on the fly. In the end the
conversion is transparent. There are even some cache-utilising c2p's that make
special use of input and output caches to c2p the data FASTER than it is possible
to copy it, on an 060. Why on earth would you then want to only copy part of the
chunky data to chipram in an effort to get the blitter to convert it faster?
There is absolutely no need and you only stand to lose.

> The most advanced consoles out there still don't handle a
> better resolutions than 320x200 or 320x400(laced) with 256 colours.

I beg to differ, I'm sure there are 640xwhatever modes on N64 and playstation, to
name just two.
 
> With the method you are mentioning, yes, but remember, any CPU with any
> C2P routine still need to do a copy from fast to chip of the converted
> buffer.

Huh? No, I don't think you know what you're talking about my friend. A chunky to
planar routine is not performed from fastram to fastram and then copied to chip.
If that is your assumption then I can see why you'd think that a blitter
conversion would help. But that is not how they work.

A chunky to planar routine is fundamentally a memory copy of the entire chunky
buffer from fastram to chipram in longwords. The only difference is that it is
also converting the data format from chunky to planar very efficiently `on the
fly', efficient enough to be transparent on all high end cpu's. There is no
additional copy to chip!

> So if you transform/copy one half and only copy the other half.
> Blitter can do the remainder half conversion.. (If you need really high
> resolutions, that is)

Nono. I see where you're going wrong now. You think that a c2p conversion is just
like some processing that gets done on the data in fastram. No, not at all. C2P
is a display method. Source is fastram, destination is chipram.

I can see why you'd think the blitter could be lifting the burden but no, it
doesn't work that way at all.
 
> >looked quite hard at the code and I don't think it's intended that a
> >fastram chunky buffer is used. A chunky buffer is reserved in chipram
> >at the end of the program.

> Again, we must complete a new routine to solve this problems.

Not possible. No need for it, absolutely no way to achieve and speed gain from
it. You only stand to lose time in setting up the blitter to do work that isn't
necessary. C2P converts fastram chunky to chipram planar. One single operation.

It's very clever!
 
> Ahh, moment! It's not viable if you aren't gonna to obtain an acceptable
> frame-rate (30 FPS are very acceptable for now).  But blitter only can
> manage 320x200 at 30 FPS, so if you want better resolutions/frame rate you
> must remember the above comments: half CPU, half blitter.

If you do half cpu half blitter you will cause the game loop to be 50% slower!

> >So that's that idea pretty much out the window.
> 
> Surely these routine is bad, we must not be forced to have the chunky
> buffer in chip-ram, this will slow down everything on faster CPU's.

Right! Exactly! And what happens when you have a fastram source? It has to be
moved to chipram in order to convert it with the blitter. What does the c2p
routine to? It copies to chipram and does the conversion transparently. So why
any further need for the blitter? None at all.

> The
> new must be better, and at must try to find the better mem -accordly to the
> CPU- to put it, or at least let the user to choose the destination of the
> chunky buffer.

Planning to write a new c2p? Good luck to you! I have no idea how they do what
they do. I just know the general facts. 

Absolutely: Blitter has no place in chunky to planar conversion.
 
[Interlaced c2p]
> Surely!  Do you remember the 'trick with sprites that will let us have
> better resolutions with a little flicker' i have mentioned, well it's
> something like this but it's an odd 'vertical interlace' to double the
> resolution at the same frame rate.  I'm no wrong, you can do this routine.

Maybe you can, but then this means having to use hardware sprites, and as I've
said people don't want to do that, and even the commodore documentation about
future compatability on the developers cd-rom states that hardware sprites should
be dropped. Also hardware sprites are too limiting in their colours.
 
> Yes, of course, we are now talking the same VIDEO amiga language :)
> Still some can need a full 640x480 multiscan resolution, but again, if you
> see the games in the most recent consoles, the high frame rate simply will
> not let you count the lines, so no-one can note the difference between a
> laced display and another that isn't.

Well that's where you're wrong because an interlaced c2p operation looks pretty
hideous for anything other than temporarily scrolling around a bitmap with not
much else happening in the processor. It is certainly not viable for 2d games as
objects just look totally sad, and it is questionable if anyone would want to use
it in 3d either. You don't gain by it, you only reallocate what you do with the
cpu, so by interlacing you halve your actual framerate.
 
> True, a 640x200 (or 640x400 laces) 8-bit resolution aren't gonna work with
> a 030/50.  But man, this is a very high resolution, you need only 320x200
> (or 320x400 laced) to do a good game display.

C2P is geared towards lores display. You cannot use higher resulutions with any
great framerate because the more DMA the resolution requires the less chipram
time there is for c2p conversion so the framerate goes down exponentially.

> Of course this would be! The most amazing video effects are done in that
> way, and they appears to be a full 640x400 resolution every 60th frame.
> (or the PAL equivalent, although the flicker is less noticeable in NTSC)

`Appear' maybe, but in fact the appearance is abysmal. It is only an optical
illusion that it seems like it's at 50fps but in fact it is still at 25, and if
you use the `saved' time to do extra processing the freamreate just starts going
down to 16fps or whatever, and interlaced c2p at 16fps is ugly.
 
> As always, we expect a good job from good guys.

Well maybe you should give up your expectations. :-o

> >to RTG has been huge. This time next year AGA will be ready to be
> >forgotten which will be great!
> 
> NO! if we can prevent it! :)

Prolong it maybe but not prevent it. And you are only one person there's so many
people out there that you will have no effect on.

> After all, the work isn't too hard, and the benefits
> for blitz game developers will be good.

Which blitz game developers? Anyone who is doing serious work is paying serious
attention to the fact that AGA has had it for `special effects'.

> Still, the better the CPU, the
> better the game. Isometric/platform type games are going to gain lots of
> CPU power with the help of AGA and the majority of the graphics cards out
> there simply can't match this.

No? A zorro3 card could do much better platformers than AGA ever could, and
better than aga-assisted could ever do as well.

Ask yourself, what /type/ of platform game are you going to do with the aga
hardware? Think for a minute. You'll have one playfield because dual playfield is
so restricting on colours. You'll have smooth scrolling but you won't have very
many things moving. You'll have hardly any background animation. You might have
more than 256 colours but really 256 is plenty anyway. You might have hardware
sprites but they're so drab and few. That's it. What else is there? If you want
to bring in the cpu you aren't in an ideal situation to use c2p anymore because
you've spent so much time working in chipram, and so any blits will be planar to
chipram and that as you agree is a mass hinderence to the cpu. So what is this
game going to turn out to be? Just like all those that have come before. It's
already been used to the limits, pushed to the max, and done to the death.

People are exploring new ways of doing their engines these days. Gone are the
days of bitplanes+blitter+sprires+copper. It's now graphicscard|AGA+c2p+cpu+more
memory. If I were gunna write a platform game these days I sure wouldn't choose
to do it in the `traditional' way. I'd want to have a few layers of parallax and
lots of animation all over the place, tonnes of baddies and special effects that
are only realy possible in chunky. The scrolling would be done in software.

Software scroll really is taking over from hardware scroll, be it with a fastram
superbitmap or a fastram buffer or a fastram tile method and c2p conversion.

When I bought my 040/25 card it was 210 quid. Now you can get them for 130. At
the time I got mine you'd be hard pushed to get an 030/50 for that price. 060's
are under 300 and still dropping. The prices are coming down, the specs are going
up, the expectations are going up, the creativity is wanting more freedom, people
want more impact and more movement. What are you going to give them? Something
like robocod? Robocod was a good game but as a game, not as an engine compared
wither other games these days. It's too flat. The shift is towards semi-3d with
2d-games now not just flat 2d objects all over the place.
 
> That's why we are not going to forget the chunky mode.  And that's the
> reason of why we must do the faster C2P routine for every CPU ever seen.

And you think we're so talented that we're going to achieve this? Not so. The
demo coders that work passionately on the chunky to planar converters are experts
on it, they know assembler inside and out. They come up with the very fast c2p
converters that we have now. You aren't going to improve on them and nor am I.
 
> When those libraries can be usable, our games will going to be the best 
> ever seen as we will have more CPU power free than the others :)

Okay. What is the fascination with having FREE cpu power? It is surely much
better to have the cpu DOING something. I think you are in love with the idea of
having free time, always wanting more free time to do stuff, but have you
considered what you might actually DO with that free time? I think you want the
free time more than you want to do something with it. Think about it. If the
blitter is handling your graphics what will the higher end cpu do? It will be
wasted.

> That's true, a big 640x400 animation can be halfed if you select the
> correct 640x200 frames. BUT.... You must be sure that your work are
> going to work in a true stable and high frame rate (60 or 50 Hz).  So,
> again, a VBlank IRQ is pretty recommended, or your display work can be
> 'desynchronizated' and this would lead to very bad results.

I can see no real gain in interlaced c2p other than to damage the quality of the
display.
 
> >I think it'd be
> >possible to therefore eliminate the verticle movement artefacts but
> >you are still left with the horizontal comb effect.
> 
> We must see it in action...

Well the thing I posted recently shows blits being done in interlaced. It doesn't
look pretty, it's not even coherent most of the time. I wouldn't want to be
looking at something like that for hours on end.

Okay.

At the end of your long message now.

Do you get it now, are you with us? There is no point getting the blitter out of
retirement.

Sorry if I sound harsh or offensive but you're not listening to the facts.

You are mistaken completely about how chunky to planar works. It
outputs directly to chipram from fastram and performs the converstaion
transparently. There is no feasible use for the blitter there. Sprites
are too limiting, copperlists are a bit hacky and won't work on
graphics cards, the blitter is slow and works only in chipram, old
tiling methods are too outdated and there is not enough time for
enough animation and movement, people want to see their graphics cards
and higher cpu's used and visably so. AGA is a display device now,
nothing more. The only parts that are used are o/s friendly hidden
copperlists that intuition handles on its own, a single hardware
sprite for the mouse pointer which is also handled entirely by
intuition, bitplane dma for the display in AGA and possibly sound DMA
for 8-bit samples via Paula. That's it. The blitter has no feasible
effectiveness anymore and the other hardware sprites are too limited.

-- 
Paul.

