@NODE "Mail_311" "Re: Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 Tue, 20 Oct 1998 16:20:54 -0600 (CST)
Date: Tue, 20 Oct 1998 16:20:54 -0600 (CST)
From: Carlos Villarroel Cortes <carlosv@redes.unam.mx>
Subject: Re: Most wanted Blitz Libs.

Paul,

After read your really horrendously looooong message i feel an odd impulse
to answer every line of your mail, but after a while of reflection, i think
it's not correct to do, after all, the blitz users interested on this theme
don't want to invest his time in these sort of pretty useless discussion.

So i will summarize the main points in your mail:

Amiga AGA hardware limits the creativity of the programmer.  The solution
is using chunky buffers to do every thing you dream with the CPU. More
over, you can transport your game to the new hardware without worry.

We all agree. No more to discuss.

With AGA only graphics stuff (blitter,display, all planar) the CPU is going
to loose more processing time if you need to use it making some cpu-blits
(planar) to obtain more bob's on screen due the overloaded chip-ram bus.
(In case you want really big bob's or hundreds of them, without considering
the sprites/dual PF capabilities that sure can help.)

Again, we agree from the begining.

About properly queud blits, yes it's been done before, in all languages but
Blitz.  About super-optimized assembler tile scrollers, again it's been
done before, but the bad way, and the best example are the games you're
mentioning, they're not exactly state of the art -16 colours, no DPF's,
slow down with small sprites- and sure they can't multitask.

About blitter assisted C2P from Chip Ram, if you do not want to support
low-end users any more, then you are in your own right.  I'm only saying
that this could be good if the work isn't too hard.

About blitter assisted C2P from Fast Ram, if you can do some register-based
C2P work while copying planar -already converted- data to chip-ram then
sure you can do other -than C2P- register-based work while copying chunky
data to chip-ram (for the blitter) but anyway, you win. :( i'm short of
time now to discuss this.) And today, this is going to be useless for
really high-end (PPC) users -even A1200-.  After all they have the money to
buy a graphics card without worry.

Mmmm.. it seems that i'm again discussing things, ok. i will say only the
next:

We are now perfectly capable of realize what's the best option to make a
game:

If we select the 'traditional' way to make an amiga game, it's because
it will work in all amigas -actual low(030down) and high(040up) end- with
some degree of quality in the gameplay/display department.  Wheter we need
to write again the main loop/graphics part -for new amigas- or not it's
something under the programmer responsability.

If we select the chunky option in search for biggest and better graphics
for high-end/future amigas then i have nothing against it, more over,
it's the future, and diversity is better in all respects. (I can't remember
me saying that chunky is bad anyway).

No more to discuss here.

But...  Any effort to help now those low-end users to make better games
must be degraded?  I don't think so.

In the best of the worlds, we all must be able to own the last and fastest
equipment, until then, please, Can we try to get the most of the AGA
hardware with a great language like Blitz?

To me, it's enought for words, it's time to go out and try to get it
working at least for the two first libraries.

Thanks for reading.




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_312" "Re: Most wanted Blitz Libs."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Tue, 20 Oct 1998 22:59:13 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 20 Oct 98 23:58:02 +0000
Subject: Re: Most wanted Blitz Libs.
Encoding: 7bit

> About blitter assisted C2P from Chip Ram, if you do not want to support
> low-end users any more, then you are in your own right.  I'm only saying
> that this could be good if the work isn't too hard.

Blitter-based or assites c2p's are only intended for use on something
up to, for example, an 030/25Mhz. Okay so there are still low-end
users and I'm not saying forget about them entirely it's just not a
specification I personally intend to work with/for anymore.
 
> About blitter assisted C2P from Fast Ram, if you can do some register-based
> C2P work while copying planar -already converted- data to chip-ram then
> sure you can do other -than C2P- register-based work while copying chunky
> data to chip-ram (for the blitter) but anyway, you win. :( i'm short of
> time now to discuss this.) And today, this is going to be useless for
> really high-end (PPC) users -even A1200-.  After all they have the money to
> buy a graphics card without worry.

There is no time to be doing ANY chipram access during a c2p
conversion. The routine has to have full unhindered access for writing
to chipram while it is converting the data to planar, so there is
nothing else you can be doing in chipram at the time, and in almost
all cases nothing you can be doing in fastram either. I'm not saying
c2p is dead already, just in a year or two it will be much less
needed. I do just think though that the low-end chunky to planar
systems are too limiting for good results. If you want to work with
the low end stick with planar methods.
 
> If we select the 'traditional' way to make an amiga game, it's because
> it will work in all amigas -actual low(030down) and high(040up) end- with
> some degree of quality in the gameplay/display department.

This is true. Although the same is also said of using chunky to planar
in which the AGA display is simply a display device, as it will work
on all Amiga's. It just so happens that working in chunky makes it
effortless to support graphics cards too.

> If we select the chunky option in search for biggest and better graphics
> for high-end/future amigas then i have nothing against it, more over,
> it's the future, and diversity is better in all respects. (I can't remember
> me saying that chunky is bad anyway).

Okay.
 
> But...  Any effort to help now those low-end users to make better games
> must be degraded?  I don't think so.

Not degraded no, but this doesn't mean therefore that the low-end is
worthy of the attention you suggest.
 
> In the best of the worlds, we all must be able to own the last and fastest
> equipment, until then, please, Can we try to get the most of the AGA
> hardware with a great language like Blitz?

Well I myself don't have the fastest equipment, only an 040/25 and
normal AGA. Even on an 030/50 though chunky to planar at 320x200 will
give better results than are possible with the blitter. That only then
leaves the lower end 030's and the 020. It is certainly not worth
supporting the 68000 specifically now as the base machine is AGA with
68020 or higher. Those who haven't upgraded their cpu and/or fastram
will expect to be in some ways limited in what is possible. But it
doesn't apply to everyone and probably in fact is only a minority
these days, according to the most recent surveys. And right now,
someone working on a new project isn't going to be finished for the
next 6-24 months perhaps and accelerators will be so much cheaper come
the release date.
 
> To me, it's enought for words, it's time to go out and try to get it
> working at least for the two first libraries.

Okay have a go with the queud blit library, you may have some joy with
it over the normal blit method. I am not sure what you mean by the
virtual bitmap library, I suppose just the tile-scroller. It is all
very well but most people write their own game engines and that
includes custom scrollers which they will likely want to tailor to
suit their needs more than you can provide with a library. Good luck
with it though.

-- 
Paul.

