@NODE "Mail_329" "Re: New Library..."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 22 Oct 1998 19:04:13 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 22 Oct 98 20:03:04 +0000
Subject: Re: New Library...
Encoding: 7bit

Rui,

> I've been thinking (NO jokes please!) and it you be very nice to have a new
> command such as FShape (Shapes stored in FastMem!) and FShapeLoad (Load shapes
> into fast). 
> It doesn't need to be great, it just needs to work...
> Let's face it, why throw away chip mem when we so much fast available...

The shape data must be in chipram otherwise the blitter cannot do
anything with it (ie it can't blit it). You could only put your shapes
in fastram if you were going to use a cpu-blit routine, or if you
planned to copy them back in before using them. The latter idea is
quite interesting although most games will only load in the graphics
they are actually going to be using anyway.
 
> I'm not sure but isn't it just a problem of changing the pointers to the shape?

Probably something like that, just a change to the cookie pointer and
the planes pointer. Although, if you do that you certainly wont be
able to use the blitter to do anything with it. You'd have to have a
cpu-blit routine.
 
> People give some input here, what do you say about it? Is it possible? Is it
> useful? Do we need it?

Possible, yes. Useful, maybe. Do we need it, sometimes.

-- 
Paul.

