@NODE "Mail_355" "Re: powerpacker problem"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    9 Oct 98 10:02:16 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University
Date: Fri, 9 Oct 1998 10:02:10 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: powerpacker problem

On 8 Oct 98, at 16:56, Curt Esser (on behalf of James Boyd) collapsed unde=
r the weight of:

> ; ppLoadData_() should put the pointer to the buffer it allocates,and ;
> the length of the buffer into *bufp and *lenp...
> 
> DEFTYPE.l *bufp,*lenp

 OK, one thing I must say is that the pointer handling of default 
type varibales (b, w, l , etc) in Blitz is more confusing than using 
pointers to structures. If I`m reading this correctly, the pp command 
returns the address of the buffer it allocates. This means that you 
need to specify the address of your pointer in the call.
 
so try:
ret.bppLoadData_(&fname$,#DECR_NONE,#MEMF_PUBLIC,&*bufp,&*lenp,-1)
 

|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_356" "Re: powerpacker problem"
          Paris Sat, 10 Oct 1998 17:53:50 +0200 (MET DST)
          Paris Sat, 10 Oct 1998 17:53:47 +0200 (MET DST)
From: Mathias PARNAUDEAU <Mathias.P@wanadoo.fr>
Date: Sat, 10 Oct 1998 17:44:57 +0100
Subject: Re: powerpacker problem

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.

This message was composed on an Amiga using the YAM mailer.
YAM is available at http://bitcom.ch/~mbeck/

--BOUNDARY.7587.2870.270834560.1
Encoding: quoted-printable

Le 08-Oct-98, Curt Esser a =E9crit:

>Hi everyone,

>I'm posting this on behalf of James Boyd, who currently has no internet
>connection. I looked at the source, but I can't seem to get the commands=
>even tokenize (see other posting).

>Can anyone help wit this?

Hi Curt,

I suppose I can answer you and help James (except if he already found :-)=

I attached the modified source.

It seems James confuses the address of the buffer with the address of the=

buffer variable (called bufp). I mean : the function ppLoadData_ gives th=
e
address of the buffer (which contains the crunched datas) IN the bufp
variable.
So, the datas are located at the address bufp, and not at &bufp.

To write the buffer on disk, this gives :

   writemem(*retopen,bufp,lenp)

and to free the memory :

   freemem_ bufp,lenp

In the source, I changed *bufp and *lenp. I called them bufp and lenp as =
long
words.

I wrote one or two other comments in the source.

And to conclude, I suppose you (James) know that ppLoadData_ just load th=
e
crunched data in the buffer (which address is in the bufp variable, I tel=
l you
again) BUT doesn't decrunch this datas. At the moment, your program just =
copy
a file (and apparently it doesn't recognize if the file is packed).

I wish all that would help you.

Regards,

                                       Mathias

-- =

email       : mathias.p@wanadoo.fr
site web : http://perso.wanadoo.fr/supersport/


--BOUNDARY.7587.2870.270834560.1
Encoding: quoted-printable

; Atem-PUP! - Attempted PowerUnPacking ;)

; attempted unpacking of a PowerPacked file by James L Boyd...
; ohmygolly@hotmail.com

; anyone know what's wrong?

; WARNING! As it is,this causes Enforcer hits and may possibly crash
; your system!!! Only run it if you know what you're doing!

; this program will take a powerpacked file and write out an
; unpacked version of the file...in theory.

; just now,it writes out a garbled file,of the correct length (ie the len=
gth
; of the original,unpacked file),but *bufp and *lenp both get the same
; values,so the file's a mess :(

; NOTE - this needs powerpacker.fd to be FDConvert'ed

; ( powerpacker.fd and docs are in Aminet - "util/libs/pplib16.lha" )

; constants
; ---------

; decrunch effects

#DECR_COL0   =3D  0
#DECR_COL1   =3D  1
#DECR_POINTER    =3D  2
#DECR_SCROLL   =3D  3
#DECR_NONE   =3D  4

; error codes

#PP_OPENERR    =3D -1
#PP_READERR    =3D -2
#PP_NOMEMORY   =3D -3
#PP_CRYPTED    =3D -4
#PP_PASSERR    =3D -5
#PP_UNKNOWNPP    =3D -6
#PP_EMPTYFILE    =3D -7

; file opening modes

#MODE_OLDFILE=3D1005   ;
#MODE_NEWFILE=3D1006   ; see "Blitz2:Developers/amigaincludes/dos/dos.bb2=
"
#MODE_READWRITE=3D1004 ;

; public memory flag

#MEMF_PUBLIC=3D(1LSL0) ; want to unpack to public memory

FindScreen 0 ; for ASLRequestFile$

; stuff for ASLRequestFile$ :
; open[x]$ refers to the PowerPacked file to open
; save[x]$ refers to the file to save

MaxLen openp$=3D192:MaxLen openf$=3D192:MaxLen savep$=3D192:MaxLen savef$=
=3D192
openp$=3D"RAM:":openf$=3D"":savep$=3D"RAM:":savef$=3D"Unpackedfile.txt"

; define some error strings for ppLoadData's error codes...

Dim error$(7)
Restore errors:For a.b=3D0 To 7:Read error$(a):Next a
errors:
Data$ "Success unpacking file!","Error opening file!","Error reading file=
!"
Data$ "Not enough memory!","This file's encrypted!","Wrong password!"
Data$ "Packed with unknown|version of PowerPacker!","Empty file!"

fname$=3DASLFileRequest$("Select a PowerPacked file :",openp$,openf$)

If openf$=3D"" Then End

; ppLoadData_() should put the pointer to the buffer it allocates,and
; the length of the buffer into *bufp and *lenp...

;DEFTYPE.l *bufp,*lenp         @ NO NEED: pointers are always longwords @=

DEFTYPE .l bufp,lenp

; right,attempt to unpack the file :

;ret.b=3DppLoadData_(&fname$,#DECR_NONE,#MEMF_PUBLIC,*bufp,*lenp,-1)
;@  ^^ ret MUST be a .l variable, so : @
ret.l=3DppLoadData_(&fname$,#DECR_NONE,#MEMF_PUBLIC,&bufp,&lenp,-1)


;Request "","Output buffer location : "+Str$(Peek.l(*bufp))+"|Output buff=
er length : "+Str$(Peek.l(*lenp)),"OK"
Request "","Output buffer location : "+Str$(bufp)+"|Output buffer length =

; ppLoadData : &fname$        - pointer to file name string
;              #DECR_NONE     - decrunch effect
;              #MEMF_PUBLIC   - type of memory to unpack into
;              *bufp          - pointer to unpacked data buffer
;              *lenp          - pointer to length of unpacked data buffer=

;              -1             - no custom password "hook"

; ret.b is the error code (a NEGATIVE number!)

; ok,now show result - works,because it recognises empty files,and passwo=
rd-
; protected files...

Request "","Atem-PUP!||"+error$(-ret),"OK"

If ret=3D0 ; 0 means no error,ie it worked...
         ; also,note that if the file is NOT PowerPacked,it goes into
         ; the buffer anyway,ie it's still a success...

newf$=3DASLFileRequest$("Save unpacked file as :",savep$,savef$)

*retopen.l=3DOpen_(&newf$,#MODE_NEWFILE) ; open a file
  If *retopen

  retlen.l=3DWrite_(*retopen,bufp,lenp) ; write the unpacked data
;@ I removed Peek.x() @

  If retlen
    Request "","Successfully saved unpacked file :||"+Str$(retlen)+" byte=
s.","OK"
  Else Request "","Uh-oh...no data written!","OK"
  EndIf

retclosed.l=3DClose_(*retopen) ; close the file

  Else Request "","User cancelled / error opening file!","Abort!":Goto Fr=
eeAndEnd
  EndIf ; from "If *retopen"...

; Request "","Close value : "+Str$(retclosed),"OK"
; ^ activate to see close_() result

; free allocated memory and quit

FreeAndEnd

If ret=3D0 Then FreeMem_ bufp,lenp

; **** I think that ^ should be " FreeMem_ Peek.l(*bufp),Peek.l(*lenp) "
; but that crashes,cos the values are wrong to start with!   ****

EndIf ; from "If Ret=3D0" ...

End

--BOUNDARY.7587.2870.270834560.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_357" "Re: PPC Blitz"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 8 Oct 1998 15:49:10 +0000
From: "Dave" <Dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: PPC Blitz
Date: Fri, 2 Jan 1998 22:39:15 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 8bit

Hi,

Just thought I`d add my thoughts about this. Both Frédéric Laboureur and
Anton Reinauer have the right idea about doing a new blitz type compiler. I
have a slight variation on that, how about a macro compiler. This takes
basic like instructions, and converts them to an asm source file, which then
can be compiled by a cli compiler. This would allow you to use your
favourite
rexx compatible text editor (BlacksEd is free, and this is what I use) to
edit your source, and then run the rexx script from a menu or key press,
which first converts the file to asm source, and if any errors, they can be
reported back to the text editor through rexx, and if not, compiled into a
program, which could be run from inside the editor (another rexx script), or
automatically by the compiler script.

You could have any macro definitions files (ie, 680x0, PPC, etc.,) to
compile to different processors (or operating systems even). The one I used
on the PC was called PDS (I think..and had the ability to have compiled
macro librarys, aswell as user librarys (simple text files containing asm
code) added on, and allowed you to include the instruction direct, or as a
routine at the end of the compiled source, so you would only include the
routines used from a library and not the whole library!

I did tinker with the idea of writing blitz in the pc macro language, but
the screens and windows would have been hard to emulate, and I`m not sure
that it`d be worth it. I did start writing (well, designing) a macro
programming language for the amiga (as the beauty of it is, once you have
designed the actual macro compiler, virtually ANY language can be written in
it....for instantance, someone could write E using a macro library, to
compile E source code for PPC)

So my advice is do that, because once you have the macro compiler, you
could compile it`s self on it (if you`d written the macro compiler in
blitz), and have the compiler in any cpu (aslong as you`ve written the macro
librarys for that cpu). I wouldn`t mind working on a project like this, as
this would mean your programming language wouldn`t become out of date (or
your compiler, as every new os, or cpu that comes along, could be catered
for using a new library of functions), and you can add new routines with
ease.

If anyone likes the idea, or is already doing this, or would like to start
a project give me an email..cos I`d like to work on this (anything future
proof is a good idea in my book!).

Dave






@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_358" "Re: PPC Blitz"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Fri, 9 Oct 1998 02:32:14 +0000
From: "Dave" <Dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: PPC Blitz
Date: Sat, 3 Jan 1998 09:26:06 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit


Hi Fred,

>    Yes but with one objection. If you give all the source code of your
libs,
>anybody will be able to copy easely your work... I'm not for that. Really,
may
>be it will be free, but hours I past to optimize some libraries, I don't
want
>than anyone can use it immediately...

basic librarys of routines (in a special non text format..sort of like
making a deflibs, so ppl can`t steal your stuff), and you have to pay them
for the full advanced librarys. So with this, you could just supply a 68k
(or PPC) library, with a few functions removed, and ask for a donation for
the full librarys (and that way, the system is free..ie the macro compiler,
but the libraries..where most of your hard work would be in, would cost them
money, but they could still use it as is, or make their own libaries!).

Dave

P.s. I like the idea of integrated developement, but this way, you could do
everything from your favourite arexx compatible text editor and save a lot
of time and pain. For things like gui creators..they could be plugins, with
rexx scripts to create files to include in your source. As for a debugger,
you could do something like the advanced blitz one (rwe??), as all you have
to do is to compile extra debug info and data and a few commands to pass to
a seperate debugger program. (ie, you compile and assemble a executable
which you run, which hooks into the debugger, and passes info, and lets you
step through...etc., through the use of extra commands compiled into the
program when you have debuger enabled)





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_359" "PPC Blitz"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 7 Oct 1998 22:35:08 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 7 Oct 98 23:32:44 +0000
Subject: PPC Blitz
Encoding: 7bit

Hi.

This talk of PPC Blitz (or basically a new compiler or language) is
very interesting. Been thinking about PPC myself recently. It would be
a hell of a lot more attractive for me to get a PPC card if there was
a decent language for it other than C and PPCASM. It'd make it far
more accessible and that could decide it for me alone. The thought of
not easily being able to program the thing is a bit of a put-off.
Having ppc modules called from an a68k program is a bit messy so it'd
be great to have programs compiled for ppc direct, especially from a
language like blitz (with improvements). It's a pity the phoenix thing
is kind of dropped but nice to see people taking up the bandwagon
again.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
