@NODE "Mail_405" "Re: Screenpattern"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 1 Oct 1998 11:48:40 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Thu, 01 Oct 1998 12:40:24 +0000
Subject: Re: Screenpattern

Hi,

> does anyone know how to realize opening a screen with a specified
> graphical pattern (as the WB-Screen does) in Blitz?

I din't know WB-Screen had a pattern. Maybe you're refering to
the WB-Window which is usually in "backdrop" mode.

There is a tag called SA_BackFill which is a pointer to a backfill
hook for the screen's Layer_Info. That might do it although working
with "hooks" is a little out of my league (in Blitz) :)

Windows also have a similar "hook" called WA_BackFill although
it's quite easy to fill the window with a pattern before you add
your gadgets (if you need gadgets) so maybe you just need to
open a full screen backdrop Window and fill it with a pattern or
picture of your choice.

Cheers,

-- 
Paul Burkey <--> http://burkey.home.ml.org <-->



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_406" "Re: Screenpattern"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 01 Oct 1998 19:22:40 -0500
Subject: Re: Screenpattern

Hi,

On 01-Oct-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
> Hi,
> 
>> does anyone know how to realize opening a screen with a specified
>> graphical pattern (as the WB-Screen does) in Blitz?
> 
> I din't know WB-Screen had a pattern. Maybe you're refering to
> the WB-Window which is usually in "backdrop" mode.

No, you actually can set a different pattern for the screen too, if you want. 
It will only show if you "unbackdrop" the WB window, and shrink it.  Seems a
bit pointless, but it can be done.
> 
> There is a tag called SA_BackFill which is a pointer to a backfill
> hook for the screen's Layer_Info. That might do it although working
> with "hooks" is a little out of my league (in Blitz) :)
> 
> Windows also have a similar "hook" called WA_BackFill although
> it's quite easy to fill the window with a pattern before you add
> your gadgets (if you need gadgets) so maybe you just need to
> open a full screen backdrop Window and fill it with a pattern or
> picture of your choice.

You can do this on a screen too, although it probably won't work on a GFX
card.

Open the screen, find it's bitmap, load the pattern as a shape,
then write a routine to caluclate the sizes, etc, and ClipBlit your shape as
needed to fill the screen's bitmap.

The backdrop window idea is better, since it would work on any system.


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




