Hello,

Does anyone know how to display a picture in hires-laced at 640x512 with 256
colours (8 bitplanes) on a normal window. I've tried this, but I just get
corrupt graphics on the screen, and when I try to quit the programme, it
says 'unable to free memory'. The biggest picture I've managed to do in
hires-laced with 8 bitplanes is 512x512. (The problems happen if I try to
make the width any bigger than 512.) 

Can someone please help me?

Here is bit of code from the programme that I have done.

Best Regards

Stuart Walker

Digital Images

e-mail:stuart@digital-images.demon.co.uk
Website:http://www.digital-images.demon.co.uk

--BOUNDARY.2015135344.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="HiresTest"

WBStartup
NoCli
Screen 0,24,""
LoadShape 0,"Space_Station_2:Station2/StationInt",0
InitCopList 0,44,256,$10008,0,256,0
BitMap 0,640,512,8
Window 0,0,0,640,512,$1800,"",0,0
ShowPalette 0
ShowBitMap 0
Blit 0,0,0
BitMaptoWindow 0,0
MouseWait
Free Palette 0
Free BitMap 0
Free Window 0
End

--BOUNDARY.2015135344.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_409" "Re: Screens"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    28 Oct 98 13:32:21 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University
Date: Wed, 28 Oct 1998 13:32:14 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Screens

On 28 Oct 98, at 12:21, Stuart Walker floundered in a pit of silicon hell:

> Does anyone know how to display a picture in hires-laced at 640x512 with
> 256 colours (8 bitplanes) on a normal window. I've tried this, but I jus=
t
> get corrupt graphics on the screen, and when I try to quit the programme=
> it says 'unable to free memory'. The biggest picture I've managed to do =
in
> hires-laced with 8 bitplanes is 512x512. (The problems happen if I try t=
o
> make the width any bigger than 512.) 
> 
> Can someone please help me?
> 
> Here is bit of code from the programme that I have done.

 Well, your code is not right. You don't want to muck about with 
coplists when you are using screens. I think you also need to use the 
long version of the screen command for 8 plane screens. Don't do a 
show bitmap if you are going to display it through a window. If its 
bitmaps you're using then use them as bitmaps. You also need to close 
windows and screens before you free them.

 Here's some code but I don't know if the flags for the screenmode 
are correct.

WBStartup
NoCLI
Screen 0,0,0,640,512,8,$8004,"g",0,1
LoadBitmap 0,"Space_Station_2:Station2/StationInt",0
Window 0,0,0,640,512,$100f,"picture",-1,-1
BitMaptoWindow 0,0
ShowPalette 0
Mousewait
Free BitMap 0
CloseWindow 0:Free Window 0
CloseScreen 0:Free Screen 0
End

|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_410" "Re: Screens"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 28 Oct 1998 17:04:25 -0500
Subject: Re: Screens

Hi David

On 28-Oct-98, David McMinn wrote:
> On 28 Oct 98, at 17:11, Notorious floundered in a pit of silicon hell:
> 
>> DM> bitmaps you're using then use them as bitmaps. You also need to close
>> DM> windows and screens before you free them.
>> 
>> Actually, there's no need to close windows if you're going to free
>> them. Blitz ][ closes them itself.
> 
> If *you're* going to free them, i.e. free them inside your program, 
> then you must definately close them before you free them. Otherwise 
> you try to free something that isn't closed and all hell breaks 
> loose. If you want blitz to do this stuff for you, don't put in code 
> for closing or freeing things, but this is a bit untidy.

Err, actually "Close Screen" and "Close Window" do exactly the same as "Free
Screen" and "Free Window" - ie, close the Screen (or window) and free it's
memory.
Use either one - no need to use both.

I've never "Closed" a window or screen, but I have "Free'd" lots of them, with
no problems.


                                    Yours electronically,
