Sorry - the phrase fascist seems to have touched a few nerves here. In 
my line of work it's an everyday word (filtering spam, newsgroups etc),
and simply means "overly restrictive". Not sure if everyone interprets
the word in the same way..

As for "my program needs to read and write files", 
a) do you need to keep them open at all times?
b) can you not do file locking to stop simultaneous writes?

Can you imagine what would happen if "proper" programs limited themselves
to a single process at once? The BBC's webserver only handling one
request at once because it "needs to read and write files" (read
html/gif files, write log files)?

Fine. If you want to restrict your program to running with a 
single instance, just write a dummy file to ram: and delete it when
you finish. Check if it exists on starting the program - if it's there
then quit straight away. But future proofing is very difficult to 
build in at a later date, and if (for example) the Amiga OS turns into
the family OS of the future, with possibilities of the program
being used by more than one person at once in a multiuser environment,
you'll have to rewrite the code.

>> Never mind the fact that I am writing this program for MY benefit and will do
>> so to suit myself.

Then that's your choice. I was merely offering an alternative point 
of view, in the interests of freedom of your user.

> Will the person who actually wrote that statement about it the program
> being fascist please own up as I'm being marked as stupid, and whilst
> I might like to ask silly questions ocassionally, I don't criticise
> other people's reasons for wanting something a particular way

But surely encouraging good programming practice is a worthwhile
endeavour? TMTOWTDI, as the perl saying goes - but some ways are
better than others.

"Please own up?" I've never hidden my identity AFAIK. I'm not
criticising, just suggesting that there's other solutions to 
the problem (writing files without corrupting/losing data) than
just putting the whole thing in a closed box.

regards,
-- 
