 There are plenty of programs that limit themselves to a single 
process at once. Commodities are a prime example, as if you run the 
program again, either the main window shows itself or it quits the 
commodity. These are proper programs, as they are in everyday use. 
Just think, multiple copies of your program all vying for the 
priority of which one receives the hotkey presses.

 And would you really want two instances of an OS scheduler ?

