@NODE "Mail_442" "Re: Stop multiple copies of program running"
Date: Mon, 12 Oct 1998 11:10:56 +0100
From: Adam Lounds <adaml@tcp.net.uk>
Subject: Re: Stop multiple copies of program running

On Mon, Oct 12, 1998 at 10:30:06AM +0100, David McMinn said:
> On 12 Oct 98, at 9:37, Adam Lounds collapsed under the weight of:
> 
> > Can you imagine what would happen if "proper" programs limited themselves
> > to a single process at once? The BBC's webserver only handling one request
> > at once because it "needs to read and write files" (read html/gif files,
> > write log files)?
> 
>  There are plenty of programs that limit themselves to a single 
> process at once. Commodities are a prime example, as if you run the 
> program again, either the main window shows itself or it quits the 
> commodity. These are proper programs, as they are in everyday use. 
> Just think, multiple copies of your program all vying for the 
> priority of which one receives the hotkey presses.
> 
>  And would you really want two instances of an OS scheduler ?

No, but the reason given by the original poster was the issue of
file contention. Resource contention is a different matter entirely, 
and that's what commodities are generally for - either managing
resources, or GUI preferences. 

Two instances of Toolmanager might be nice if the author had restricted
the program to only running a single toolbar. Many scenarios will
actively encourage running more than one process for similar tasks - 
if (in our example) we could run a separate thread/process/whatever
you want to call it for each toolbar, or each window, or each *keyboard*
(keep your options open for future OSes...), it makes having a true
Multiprocessor OS much easier to implement. Look at the way Be does it, 
for example. Takes multithreading to extremes, the result of which
is that the performance increase from one to two to three processors
is very linear, as it should be. But if you go down the other route, 
having a single, megalomaniacal process which tries to do everything
at once, you don't get much performance increase by adding a new processor, 
as your bloated code has to run as a single process.

In your case, how's about running a process for *each key*? No vying
for priorities there... (treating the qualifier keys as a separate
issue? hmmm.) A decent OS like the Amiga's can handle large amounts
of processes without much performance hit, so why not?

I'm not saying that this would be better on the Amiga
OS, or necessarily on any other. I'm just saying that in *most*
cases, There's More Than One Way To Do It. And rejecting any method 
out of hand is a form of tunnel vision, and should be discouraged.

Admittedly, most programs are easier to code in Blitz as a single 
process, but I thought excessive pride (hubris) was one of the three
virtues of a programmer, and making things the cool way isn't always
the easiest option. The easiest way isn't always the best, and the
best way is not always the fastest.

regards,
-- 
Adam Lounds                     | Email: adaml@tcp.net.uk
Network Assistant               | Tel: +44 1703 571300
Total Connectivity Providers    | WWW: http://www.tcp.co.uk/


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_443" "Re: Stop multiple copies of program running"
From: Eoghann Irving <eoghann@thenet.co.uk>
Date: Mon, 12 Oct 1998 15:21:19 +0100
Subject: Re: Stop multiple copies of program running

Hi Adam :)

On 12-Oct-98, Adam Lounds wrote:

> Sorry - the phrase fascist seems to have touched a few nerves here. In 
> my line of work it's an everyday word (filtering spam, newsgroups etc),
> and simply means "overly restrictive". Not sure if everyone interprets
> the word in the same way..

No harm done.  Fascist has much stronger connotations as far as I'm concerned
and I don't think I would ever use it outside of a political context.

There is a tendency to use extreme words to describe much less extreme
situations.  Things can't be good they have to be wonderfull or amazing etc. 

I tend to go by dictionary definitions myself.

> As for "my program needs to read and write files", 
> a) do you need to keep them open at all times?
> b) can you not do file locking to stop simultaneous writes?

All of them open at all times? Probably not.  But a variety of files are
opened, read to and writen to at various points while the program runs. 
Simultaneous writes is not the only problem, although it would be the most
severe one.

For a start one of the files written to is a logfile which I find extremely
useful for debugging.  But that only makes sense if the log is from one
program.

Then there is the fact there are two prefs files which are read from and
written to at various intervals.  One stores window locations and sizes so
multiple copies of a program would require multiple copies of this file or it
serves no useful purpose.

Then there is the main prefs file which stores URL locations, titles, the
date the page was last checked and various other information.  This
information is also updated as the program runs.

I COULD write procedures to get round all this but I can't see even a SINGLE
reason to do so.

The program is called up while you are online, runs automatically checking
each URL in turn then exits sending an HTML page to the browser of your
choice.  Why would anyone wish to check the same URLs twice simultaneously?

The resulting program would be far far bigger than it currently is, for no
obvious gain.

> Can you imagine what would happen if "proper" programs limited themselves
> to a single process at once? The BBC's webserver only handling one
> request at once because it "needs to read and write files" (read
> html/gif files, write log files)?

That is a multi-user situation, this is not

Try running two copies of YAM.  This program does not hang around on your
screen open for ages.  It runs, it exits.  The Config program MIGHT benefit
from being run multiple times, although I can't think why for that either.

> But future proofing is very difficult to 
> build in at a later date, and if (for example) the Amiga OS turns into
> the family OS of the future, with possibilities of the program
> being used by more than one person at once in a multiuser environment,
> you'll have to rewrite the code.

Its written in Blitz it has no future on a new AmigaOS.  It would require a
re-write anyway.

> Then that's your choice. I was merely offering an alternative point 
> of view, in the interests of freedom of your user.

But what I'm telling you is that I AM my user.  I wrote it for me.  For my
personal use.

I spent a year trying to persuade "real" programmers to create this program
because I thought it would be useful. They weren't interested so I wrote it
myself. Very few people that I've described it to think there is any point to
it although I personally use it daily.  I had several beta testers for a
while 
but only 2 of them ever bothered to comment on it.

If I ever do release a version of it, it will be freeware.  The program works
the way it works because thats how I like it to behave.

-- 
Eoghann Irving
