Date: Tue, 13 Oct 1998 09:50:43 +0100
From: Adam Lounds <adaml@tcp.net.uk>
Subject: Re: Stop multiple copies of program running

On Tue, Oct 13, 1998 at 09:17:04PM +1200, Anton Reinauer said:
> On 12-Oct-98, Adam Lounds wrote:
> 
> >for example. Takes multithreading to extremes, the result of which
> >is that the performance increase from one to two to three processors
> >is very linear, as it should be. But if you go down the other route, 
> >having a single, megalomaniacal process which tries to do everything
> >at once, you don't get much performance increase by adding a new
> >processor, 
> >as your bloated code has to run as a single process.
> 
>   One point to consider here is games- most games will not want more
> than one copy of itself running, as it may be impossible to run more
> than one copy on a machine because of limited resources on current
> machines (or a worry of crashing the machine, making the game unstable)-
> and there are only 2 joystick ports etc.

This can be overcome by adding more joystick ports, no? And 
allocation of limited resources is similar to allocating sound 
channels on the current Amiga architecture. 

Alternatively, why not do it like Be do, and have the data from the
joystick port a sort of data "service" which any process can 
"subscribe" to? So you could play two different games with 
one joystick...

As with the file contention issue, most of the problems arise with 
output rather than input if you think about it carefully - if
you consider your program as a pipe, you can parse the input 
yourself in any way you like. But if your output gets confused
then whatever is looking at the "out" end will get confused. Whether
it's a text reader or a file system, you need to make sure your
output is properly organised.

> Any multi-user capibilities
> have to be specifically programed into the program (ie: split screen for
> two players).

Only if you want the two players to interact with each other. If 
you just want a situation where two people can play games on a 
21" monitor at once, there's not much more programming that needs doing.

<snip multi monitors & keyboards>

>   Another point to mention here is, until very recently MS Internet
> Explorer and Netscape, both could only put up a second web page by
> loading and running a whole new copy of itself, whereas Amiga browsers
> (and Opera) just opened a new Window. Considering the size of those
> browsers, that was a terrible waste af resources! 

Not always... Think multiprocessing, and then think crash protection.
If you have many tasks running rather than just the one, then a 
crash in one "window" won't bring all the other windows down with it.

IE4 still seems to set up a new task for each window, although if the
core process goes down the whole lot goes. Unless you set each window
as a different task, it makes swapping idle tasks to disk more
difficult (virtual memory swapping that is.)

Sorry if this is getting a little off topic... I suppose i'm just 
trying to reiterate the point that there's almost always more
than one way to skin a cat. And discussion of what should be in the 
new Amiga OS is at least *slightly* relevant.

regards,
-- 
