>>   Another point to mention here is, until very recently MS Internet
>> Explorer and Netscape, both could only put up a second web page by
>> loading and running a whole new copy of itself, whereas Amiga
browsers
>> (and Opera) just opened a new Window. Considering the size of those
>> browsers, that was a terrible waste af resources! 

>Not always... Think multiprocessing, and then think crash protection.
>If you have many tasks running rather than just the one, then a 
>crash in one "window" won't bring all the other windows down with it.

  Amigas don't crash though ;-)

>IE4 still seems to set up a new task for each window, although if the
>core process goes down the whole lot goes. Unless you set each window
>as a different task, it makes swapping idle tasks to disk more
>difficult (virtual memory swapping that is.)

  Interesting!

>Sorry if this is getting a little off topic... I suppose i'm just 
>trying to reiterate the point that there's almost always more
>than one way to skin a cat. And discussion of what should be in the 
>new Amiga OS is at least *slightly* relevant.

  No, it's been very interesting! We all should be thinking about these
concepts, as OS5 will have support for some of these things, like
multiple monitors etc.

