@NODE "Mail_449" "strange Blitz/YAM problem"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 12 Oct 1998 19:20:03 -0500
Subject: strange Blitz/YAM problem

Hi Everyone,

Sorry, this isn't really Blitz related I suppose.  But I know some of you use
YAM, and (probably) all use the Blitz compiler, so maybe you have run into
this too, or have some ideas.

I have the most recent YAM beta.  Mostly, it works perfectly.  But if I run my
Blitz compiler (actually, it happens if I just run the editor, without even
compiling anything) YAM is garuanteed to crash.  The crash happens immediately
after uploading or downloading my email.  Right after the transfer window
closes.

If I run enforcer first, the crash is avoided - but I get an enforcer hit
"long read from 0000".

Any ideas?  Oh, it isn't only after running Blitz that this happens.  Some
other programs will cause this too, some not.  For example, it will also
happen if I run Ppaint first.  But not if I run Brilliance.

And if I re-boot the system before running YAM, everything is OK again...

Thanks for any help....


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_450" "Re: Strange Problem - AGAIN"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
        Mike Delling <tranquilizer@mike.ruhr.de>
Date: Fri, 02 Oct 1998 05:38:17 -0500
Subject: Re: Strange Problem - AGAIN

Hi Mike,

On 30-Sep-98, Mike Delling wrote:

> Yesterday I tried my game on a blizzard 030 card and I was wondered about
the
> result. The game runs very, very well constantly in 25fps. But why does my
060
> slows the game down?? All caches are taken on and VBR is set into Fastram.
> When I start my game without running MCP in background the game does only
> appear in less then 5fps. That can not be!

First, the most obvious, make sure Runtime Errors is off in the compiler
options.  Otherwise everything will slow down.

It sounds like maybe a cache thing.  I use MCP, and one of the functions is
the ability to set certain of your caches off/on.  Check these settings -
maybe not all caches are on, or maybe the program runs better with some caches
off.  Look how it is set in the version that runs best, then try the same
settings on the other machine.

I think the main speed difference of the various processors is the use of the
caches, so look here first.



                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
