@NODE "Mail_462" "Re: to # or not to #"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    2 Oct 98 09:14:43 GMT+1
From: "David McMinn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University
Date: Fri, 2 Oct 1998 09:14:00 +0100
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: to # or not to #

On 1 Oct 98, at 23:41, Andrew Drays collapsed under the weight of:

> what the heck is the # for.. like 
> 
> #scrollers=3D20
> 
> whhat is that doing??!?

 I know the manual has a bad reputation but it does explain this. 
#blah is a constant which an integer number. Everywhere you use this 
constant in your program it is replaced (at compile time) by what it 
is equal to, i.e.

#blah=3D20
Nprint #blah

would get turned into

Nprint 20

at compile time.

 Use it if you are using one number specifically for a single purpose 
the whole way through your program for example for the (fixed) width 
of a shape collision zone. This way when you want to change your 
program you only have to change the #blah=3D20 line instead of having 
to change the <insert large number> of lines using this number.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


@ENDNODE
