@NODE "Mail_470" "triple buffers"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 21 Oct 1998 21:09:15 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 21 Oct 98 22:07:09 +0000
Subject: triple buffers
Encoding: 7bit

Hi.

I've encounter a wierd thing that happens when you don't use a VWait.

If you were using triple buffering you would not encounter this thing,
because there is absolutely no way that you will ever see any drawing
occuring in the spare buffer.

However, if you only have a double-buffered display and you don't have
a VWait, you DO see rendering occuring in the displayed buffer. This
happens because the routine starts to render to that buffer before the
verticle blank has finished.

This particularly applies where c2p is concerned because often the aim
is not to have to wait for the verticle blank.

So it isn't simply that you can do away with a VWait and hope that
everything will work fine. Without a VWait you *HAVE* to implement a
triple buffer otherwise it is very likely that rendering will begin on
the displayed screen before the copperlist has had a chance, after a
verticle blank period, to display the `hidden' buffer.

This is a little bit annoying as I found that even though I had a
double-buffer for the display I was still seeing glitches. Searched
through my code for ages trying to find a possibly bug or fault in the
algorithm. But it worked perfectly when I put in a VWait.

I've gotta now recode my routines to work in up to three buffers,
which for an interlaced c2p that takes six frames to build a full
picture, could get somewhat messy.

Just thought I's mention this in case anyone didn't know about it, but
probably it's just me not fully comprehending the reasons for
triple-buffering.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



