@NODE "Mail_475" "Re: Variables in Asm functions"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Fri, 30 Oct 1998 20:54:56 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 30 Oct 98 20:36:23 +0000
Subject: Re: Variables in Asm functions
Encoding: 7bit

> Hi all,
> 
> I want to make an ASM function and I need to declare functions inside. What is
> the way ? Declare them at the end of the function (and before AsmExit) as
> dc.b, other ?
> 
> Any ideas ? They're welcome.

Firstly and dc.b's are global regardless of wether you put them inside
functions, statements or what the heck. That's due to the fact that
part of assembler language is the ability to access everything
everywhere. That also means you can jump up and down to your hearts
content regardless of the order of routines.

I'm not sure what you mean by functions. If you mean assembler
subroutines you can put them wherever you like. AsmExit is kinda like
an RTS or a Pop Proc, ie it exits the asm function/statement. I
usually put subroutines after it but it makes no different so long as
you know where your program is going to exit.

-- 
Paul.

