@NODE "Mail_479" "WBBlit"
>X-Dummy: YES
X-ZC-VIA: 19981005000000S+2@dame.de
Subject: WBBlit
From: Robocop@dame.de (Frank Otto)
Date: Mon,  5 Oct 1998 10:28:58 +0100
X-Gateway: ZCONNECT dame.de [UUWORLD RFC/ZC V2.2 SER#A4583577]

Hi,

there have been some discussions about blitting shapes on RTG screens. This was
possible with "WBlit" but a buffered WBlit was missing. What do you think about
this code I wrote:

Statement WBBlit{buffer,shap,x,y}
; Scroll x,y,16,16,0,0,buffer

  Dim dot(256)
  For j=0 To 15
  For i=0 To 15
    dot(j*16+i)=Point(i+x,j+y)
  Next
  Next

  WBlit shap,x,y

  Use BitMap buffer
  Boxf 0,0,16,16,0

  For j=0 To 15
  For i=0 To 15
    Plot i,j,dot(j*16+i)
  Next
  Next
  Use BitMap db

End Statement

This grabs an area of a bitmap and copies it to a bitmap of a shape. Before you
can use this code you have to:

Initialise some shapes (this does not work with "InitShapes" on my Amiga - GetAShape
also works) and make some 'dummy' bitmaps for those shapes (ShapesBitmap).

Ok, A short explanation:

Before blitting your shape (WBlit shap,x,y) my statement grabs a part of the bitmap
using the Point-command and stores it in the dot-Dim. Then the bitmap of an 'empty'
shape is used, this shape has the number 'buffer' and is at first cleared (Boxf)
that's important if it's not empty next time you use the statement. Then the Dim
'dot' is written back on this other bitmap (which is the buffer shape). And finally
the old bitmap is used again.

To 'unbuffer' your WBBlitted shape use WBlit buffer,x,y.

As you may have noticed, I tried to copy the bitmap using the Scroll command which
would make things a lot easier but I could not get it working if I used the bitmap
of the shape ('buffer'). Hmmm..(?)

Also, since this code is just an idea, I don't know if it would work because
the shapes are blitted on windows and not bitmaps. So a 'ShowRTGBitmap' won't work and
we still had a single buffered display :(



Any suggestions?

--
Frank
Marblelous 2 News: http://marblelous2.home.ml.org



@ENDNODE
