@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_486" "Re: why asmexit?"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 14 Oct 1998 19:24:09 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 14 Oct 98 15:26:13 +0000
Subject: Re: why asmexit?
Encoding: 7bit

> 
> Does anyone know what ASMEXIT t really does?
> Until today all my inline-ASM-Statements worked
> without using amsexit. Did i miss something?

AsmExit is only used for a `pure assembler' statement. If you are
using asm inline in your program in amongst normal blitz instructions,
then you don't need an AsmExit. It is possible, however, to write a
statement or function which contains ONLY assembler instructions, in
which parameters are passed in data registers. When you do this you
have to end the statement with an AsmExit which is kind of an rts or
something but probably does some other things to keep things working
properly.

-- 
Paul.

