@NODE "Mail_488" "Re: wordwrap problem"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 19 Oct 1998 13:41:15 -0500
Subject: Re: wordwrap problem

Hi Rudy,

On 18-Oct-98, Rudolf Sanchez wrote:
> Hi Blitz Pals:
> 
> I had heard of some Blitz commands for word-wrap, however I have looked at
> the commands and none of them look specifically for word-wrapping text.
> Does anyone have a routine for this?
> 

The example for a text-viewer in a window, found on my web site, has a
word-wrapping routine in it.  It uses the system's "TextFit_" command, and
will work with any font, even proportional ones.

I don't know of any Blitz commands that do word-wrapping.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_489" "Re: wordwrap problem"
From: eNTiTy <entity@zeelandnet.nl>
Date: Mon, 19 Oct 1998 21:55:35 +0100
Subject: Re: wordwrap problem

On 19-oct-98, Rudolf Sanchez wrote:

> Hi Blitz Pals:
> 
> I had heard of some Blitz commands for word-wrap, however I have looked at
> the commands and none of them look specifically for word-wrapping text.
> Does anyone have a routine for this?
> 

Yes I have coded one some time ago, here it is

;
; Wraps (string) onto multiple rows of max (wrap) chars
; (size remains the same, this function only replaces some spaces
;  in the string with EOLs).
;
 NEWTYPE.byte
   n.b
 End NEWTYPE

 Function.s WordWrap{string.s, wrap.l}
   *byte.byte = &string
   pl.l=Len(string)
   If pl>wrap
     *prev.byte = &string
     *curr.byte = &string
     pos  .l = 0
     ww_continue:
     *byte+1: pos+1
     If *byte\n=32
       *prev=*curr: *curr=*byte
       If pos>wrap
         If *prev>&string
           *prev\n=10: pos=0
         EndIf
       EndIf
     EndIf
     If *byte<pl Then Goto ww_continue
   EndIf
   Function Return string


It works by replacing spaces just before x*wraplength with linefeeds. It's
not particularly smart (it keeps spaces at the start of the line, etc) but
it is reasonably fast and works just fine for me :)




@ENDNODE
