@NODE "Mail_493" "Re: Zoom"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 14 Oct 1998 20:43:21 -0500
Subject: Re: Zoom

Hi Luca,

On 04-Sep-95, Luca Carminati wrote:
> On 13-Ott-98, David McMinn wrote:
> 
>> On 12 Oct 98, at 21:04, Luca Carminati collapsed under the weight of:
> 
>>> is there a way to obtain the alternate position and size (zoom) of an open
>>> window?
> 

>> If you want to make the window go to those dimensions, use 
>> ZipWindow(Peek.l(Addr Window(#windownum))).
> 
> I don't need to do that. My program is iconifyable (or iconifiable? or
> iconifable?) and when the user double-clicks on the appicon, not only the
> window should be reopened at the previous position/size, but also the
> alternate position/size should be remembered.
> 
> Any other idea?

Why not just save the current settings into two sets of variables when the
window is zoomed, unzoomed, or closed (iconified)?

One set for last zoomed, one for last unzoomed.  Then you can always return to
the last sizes and positions used.  And remember the other sizes too.

You can get these with the WindowX, WindowY, WindowWidth, and WindowHeight
commands.


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_494" "Re: Zoom"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 15 Oct 1998 16:15:03 -0500
Subject: Re: Zoom

Hi Luca,

On 15-Oct-98, Luca Carminati wrote:
> On 14-Ott-98, Curt Esser wrote:
> 
>>>>> is there a way to obtain the alternate position and size (zoom) of an
>>>>> open
>>>>> window?

>>> Any other idea?
> 
>> Why not just save the current settings into two sets of variables when the
>> window is zoomed, unzoomed, or closed (iconified)?
> 
>> One set for last zoomed, one for last unzoomed.  Then you can always return
>> to
>> the last sizes and positions used.  And remember the other sizes too.
> 
>> You can get these with the WindowX, WindowY, WindowWidth, and WindowHeight
>> commands.
> 
> Yes, but how can I know if the user is moving/resizing the zoomed window
> instead of the unzoomed window? My window is zoomable and resizable, and I
> seem that the value of the zoom event is the same as the resize event (that
is
> '2').

OK, now I see the problem.  One other way would be when you iconofy the
program, just take the current size & position and save them.  Then instead of
closing the window completely, make it shrink to 1 x 1 pixel.

When you re-open, just used your saved settings.  Intuition still remembers
the other size and if the window is zoomed or not until you close the window
completely.

The only other way would be to read the values from the window structure
itself, but I don't know how to do this.  And you would also need to replace
these values into the window structure when you re-open, since this all
disappears when the window is closed down.  

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
